Wilson and American culture.\"], ''[[The New Yorker]]'', August 8, 2005. Accessed August 9, 2007. \"He liked to say that he was a man of the nineteenth century \u2014he was born in 1895, in Red Bank, New Jersey\u2014and to explain that his values and assumptions, his whole understanding of literary and intellectual life, were products of a particular moment.\"</ref>\n* [[David Wojnarowicz]] (1954\u20131992), painter, photographer, writer, filmmaker, performance artist and AIDS activist.<ref>Kimmelman, Michael. [https://www.nytimes.com/1992/07/24/arts/david-wojnarowicz-37-artist-in-many-media.html \"David Wojnarowicz, 37, Artist in Many Media\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 24, 1992. Accessed January 15, 2015. \"An abused child and a teen-age street hustler, Mr. Wojnarowicz made much of his personal history in the social margins in his art and writings. He was born in Red Bank, N.J., ran away from home, lived on the streets, and eventually graduated from the High School of Music and Art in Manhattan.\"</ref>\n* [[Alexander Woollcott]] (1887\u20131943), writer and critic born at the nearby [[North American Phalanx]] utopian community.<ref>Meehan, Thomas. [https://www.nytimes.com/1976/05/16/archives/at-last-the-star-of-the-show-smart-aleck.html \"At last the star of the show; Smart Aleck\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', May 16, 1976. Accessed November 7, 2018. \"The son of a deadbeat father and a doting mother, Woollcott, Teichmann tells us, grew up in a commune called the Phalanx, in Red Bank, N.J., where he was born in 1887, and throughout his life, perhaps because of his happy early exposure to communal living, he had an almost psychopathic fear of being alone.\"</ref>\n* [[Jeff Wulkan]] (born 1983), entrepreneur, CEO of Bikini Barbers and reality TV star of ''[[Bikini Barbershop]]''.<span style=\"color:blue;\">'''(B)'''</span>{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n* [[Dave Wyndorf]] (born 1956), songwriter, guitarist, singer and [[Monster Magnet]] bandleader.<ref>Amorosi, A. D. [http://www.citypaper.net/articles/073098/20Q.shtml \"20 Questions: David Wyndorf\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071202074404/http://www.citypaper.net/articles/073098/20Q.shtml |date=December 2, 2007 }}, ''[[Philadelphia City Paper]]'', July 30, 1998. Accessed June 26, 2008. \"I rang Wyndorf at his home in Red Bank, New Jersey, for the answer.\"</ref>\n* [[Young Rising Sons]], alternative rock band.<ref>Olivier, Bobby. [http://www.nj.com/entertainment/music/index.ssf/2014/12/must-hear_nj_young_rising_sons_return_home_with_major_record_deal.html \"Must-hear N.J.: Young Rising Sons return home with major record deal\"], NJ Advance Media for [[NJ.com]], December 9, 2014. Accessed May 15, 2016. \"Young Rising Sons, a buoyant pop-rock band from Red Bank, were one of those hopeful groups for five years, playing the New Jersey-New York circuit and waiting for the stars to align. \"</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage|Red Bank}}\n* [http://www.redbanknj.org/ Borough of Red Bank official website]\n* [http://www.rbb.k12.nj.us/ Red Bank Borough Public Schools]\n* [http://www.redbankgreen.com Red Bank Green, Hyperlocal news and features]\n* [http://redbanknj.org/history.html Red Bank, New Jersey history]\n* [http://www.redbankrivercenter.org/ Red Bank RiverCenter]\n* [http://www.redbank.com/ Community website for Red Bank, New Jersey]\n\n{{Monmouth County, New Jersey}}\n\n{{Geographic Location\n | Centre    = Borough of Red Bank\n | North     = [[Middletown Township, New Jersey|Middletown Township]]\n | Northeast = [[Fair Haven, New Jersey|Fair Haven]]\n | East      = [[Little Silver, New Jersey|Little Silver]]\n | Southeast = \n | South     = [[Shrewsbury Township, New Jersey|Shrewsbury Township]]\n | Southwest = [[Tinton Falls, New Jersey|Tinton Falls]]\n | West      = \n | Northwest = \n}}\n\n[[Category:Red Bank, New Jersey| ]]\n[[Category:1908 establishments in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Borough form of New Jersey government]]\n[[Category:Boroughs in Monmouth County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1908]]\n", "name_user": "Red dwarf", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Bank,_New_Jersey"}
{"title_page": "Flash Pose", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 song by Pabllo Vittar and Charli XCX}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name = Flash Pose\n| type = single\n| artist = [[Pabllo Vittar]] featuring [[Charli XCX]]\n| EP = 111 1 and the album [[111 (Pabllo Vittar album)|111]]\n| cover = Pabllo Vittar ft. Charli XCX - Flash Pose (official single cover).png\n| alt = \n| released = 25 July 2019\n| recorded = \n| genre = <!-- Sourced in the \"Composition\" section. --> [[Electropop]]\n| format = \n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| label = [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony Music Brazil]]\n| writer = \n* [[AlunaGeorge|Aluna Francis]]\n* Arthur Marques\n* Charli XCX\n* Maffalda\n* Pablo Bispo\n* Rodrigo Gorky\n* Zebu\n| producer = Brabo Music Team\n| chronology = Pabllo Vittar\n| prev_title = Garupa\n| prev_year = 2019\n| next_title = Parab\u00e9ns\n| next_year = 2019\n| misc = {{Extra chronology\n| artist = Charli XCX\n| type = single\n| prev_title = [[Gone (Charli XCX and Christine and the Queens song)|Gone]]\n| prev_year = 2019\n| title = Flash Pose\n| year = 2019\n| next_title = [[Click (Charli XCX song)#No Boys Remix|Click (No Boys Remix)]]\n| next_year = 2019\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|rZVhR399IoA|\"Flash Pose\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Flash Pose'''\" is a song by Brazilian singer and drag queen [[Pabllo Vittar]] featuring English singer-songwriter [[Charli XCX]]. It was released on 25 July 2019 as the lead single off of Vittar's ''111 1'' EP and ''[[111 (Pabllo Vittar album)|111]]'' album. The track is Charli XCX and Vittar's second collaboration, following \"I Got It\", which appears on Charli's ''[[Pop 2 (mixtape)|Pop 2]]'' mixtape and is followed by \"Shake It\", on the album ''[[Charli (album)|Charli]]''.\n\n== Background ==\nIn an interview with ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', Vittar explained his inspiration behind making the song entirely in English, saying \"I did a Pride tour in the U.S. and Canada this year, and there were a lot of fans there. They try to learn Portuguese so they can sing and communicate with me, so it's time for me to learn to speak their language too, right?\"<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web |last1=Blynn |first1=Alex |title=Pabllo Vittar Talks Representing Queer Brazilians, Working With Charli XCX On 'Flash Pose' |url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/news/pride/8524069/pabllo-vittar-interview-charli-xcx |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Composition ==\n\"Flash Pose\" is Vittar's first English-language track. Musically, it is a \"self-assured, club-ready\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Legaspi |first1=Althea |title=Pabllo Vittar, Charli XCX Are Camera-Ready on New Song 'Flash Pose' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/pabllo-vittar-charli-xcx-song-flash-pose-listen-863827/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=25 July 2019}}</ref> [[electropop]] composition influenced by [[house music]].<ref name=\"G1\">{{cite web |last1=Matos |first1=Tha\u00eds |title=Pabllo Vittar debuts in English with Charli XCX, but loses 'Brazilianness' by focusing on the international market |url=https://g1.globo.com/pop-arte/musica/noticia/2019/07/30/pabllo-vittar-estreia-em-ingles-com-charli-xcx-foca-no-mercado-internacional-mas-perde-brasilidade.ghtml |website=[[G1 (website)|G1]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=Portugese |date=30 July 2019}}</ref> It features a \"percussive, [[Electronic music|electronic]]-tinged chorus\",<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kaye |first1=Ben |title=Charli XCX teams with Pabllo Vittar for \"Flash Pose\": Stream |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/07/charli-xcx-pabllo-vittar-flash-pose-stream/ |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=26 July 2019}}</ref> \"driving\" beats<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nied |first1=Mike |title=Yes, Girl! Charli XCX Links Up With Pabllo Vittar On \"Flash Pose\" |url=https://www.idolator.com/7839187/yes-girl-charli-xcx-links-up-with-pabllo-vittar-on-flash-pose?view-all |website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=25 July 2019}}</ref> and \"a roiling verse about wearing vintage Versace and party-hopping in a bright pink car ''a la'' Malibu Barbie\" by Charli XCX.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pulgar |first1=E.R. |title=Drag Superstar Pabllo Vittar Celebrates Life on Trilingual New EP, '111 1' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/pabllo-vittar-brazil-drag-new-ep-1111-919837/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=4 December 2019}}</ref> Tha\u00eds Matos of Brazilian website [[G1 (website)|G1]] noted the absence of the [[tecnobrega]] or [[Funk carioca|funk]] sound Vittar's previous releases incorporated.<ref name=\"G1\"/>\n\n== Music video ==\nThe \"Flash Pose\" music video premiered one day after the song on the [[Grindr]] app, and later, on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Faia |first1=Amanda |title=Pabllo Vittar and Charli XCX release video for \"Flash Pose\" |url=https://portalpopline.com.br/pabllo-vittar-e-charli-xcx-lancam-clipe-para-flash-pose/ |website=POPline |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=Portugese |date=26 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Pabllo Vittar |title=Pabllo Vittar ft. Charli XCX - Flash Pose (Official Music Video) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rZVhR399IoA |website=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=26 July 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\nMike Wass of [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] called the song a highlight on its parent album.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wass |first1=Mike |title=Stream: Pabllo Vittar's '111' Album Is Jam-Packed With Bangers |url=https://www.idolator.com/7908473/stream-pabllo-vittars-111-album-is-jam-packed-with-bangers?view-all |website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>  Suzy Exposito of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' placed the music video on a list of the 10 best Latin music videos of July.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Exposito |first1=Suzy |title=Play It Again: The 10 Best Latin Music Videos of July |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/july-latin-music-videos-anuel-aa-residente-pabllo-vittar-865695/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=31 July 2019}}</ref> Alex Blynn praised the single, writing \"The track feels eminently danceable, fun as hell and offer[ing] a new take on classic Pabllo-sounds\".<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n\n== Release history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Region\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Format\n! scope=\"col\" | Label\n! scope=\"col\" | {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Various\n| 25 July 2019\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony Music Brazil]]\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=Flash Pose - Single by Pabllo Vittar & Charli XCX on Apple Music |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/flash-pose-single/1472452297 |website=[[Apple Music]] |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Flash Pose by Pabllo Vittar, Charli XCX on Spotify |url=https://open.spotify.com/album/7a8LBp4khqUFgSc4j8tVgN?si=40OMbL4TS7Cgiz2EXLROPA |website=[[Spotify]] |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Charli XCX}}\n\n[[Category: Pabllo Vittar songs]]\n[[Category: Charli XCX songs]]\n[[Category: 2019 songs]]\n[[Category: 2019 singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 song by Pabllo Vittar and Charli XCX}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name = Flash Pose\n| type = single\n| artist = [[Pabllo Vittar]] featuring [[Charli XCX]]\n| EP = 111 1 and the album [[111 (Pabllo Vittar album)|111]]\n| cover = Pabllo Vittar ft. Charli XCX - Flash Pose (official single cover).png\n| alt = \n| released = 25 July 2019\n| recorded = \n| genre = <!-- Sourced in the \"Composition\" section. --> [[Electropop]]\n| format = \n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| label = [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony Music Brazil]]\n| writer = \n* [[AlunaGeorge|Aluna Francis]]\n* Arthur Marques\n* Charli XCX\n* Maffalda\n* Pablo Bispo\n* Rodrigo Gorky\n* Zebu\n| producer = Brabo Music Team\n| chronology = Pabllo Vittar\n| prev_title = Garupa\n| prev_year = 2019\n| next_title = Parab\u00e9ns\n| next_year = 2019\n| misc = {{Extra chronology\n| artist = Charli XCX\n| type = single\n| prev_title = [[Gone (Charli XCX and Christine and the Queens song)|Gone]]\n| prev_year = 2019\n| title = Flash Pose\n| year = 2019\n| next_title = [[Click (Charli XCX song)#No Boys Remix|Click (No Boys Remix)]]\n| next_year = 2019\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|rZVhR399IoA|\"Flash Pose\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Flash Pose'''\" is a song by Brazilian singer and draq queen [[Pabllo Vittar]] featuring English singer-songwriter [[Charli XCX]]. It was released on 25 July 2019 as the lead single off of Vittar's ''111 1'' EP and ''[[111 (Pabllo Vittar album)|111]]'' album. The track is Charli XCX and Vittar's second collaboration, following \"I Got It\", which appears on Charli's ''[[Pop 2 (mixtape)|Pop 2]]'' mixtape and is followed by \"Shake It\", on the album ''[[Charli (album)|Charli]]''.\n\n== Background ==\nIn an interview with ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', Vittar explained his inspiration behind making the song entirely in English, saying \"I did a Pride tour in the U.S. and Canada this year, and there were a lot of fans there. They try to learn Portuguese so they can sing and communicate with me, so it's time for me to learn to speak their language too, right?\"<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web |last1=Blynn |first1=Alex |title=Pabllo Vittar Talks Representing Queer Brazilians, Working With Charli XCX On 'Flash Pose' |url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/news/pride/8524069/pabllo-vittar-interview-charli-xcx |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Composition ==\n\"Flash Pose\" is Vittar's first English-language track. Musically, it is a \"self-assured, club-ready\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Legaspi |first1=Althea |title=Pabllo Vittar, Charli XCX Are Camera-Ready on New Song 'Flash Pose' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/pabllo-vittar-charli-xcx-song-flash-pose-listen-863827/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=25 July 2019}}</ref> [[electropop]] composition influenced by [[house music]].<ref name=\"G1\">{{cite web |last1=Matos |first1=Tha\u00eds |title=Pabllo Vittar debuts in English with Charli XCX, but loses 'Brazilianness' by focusing on the international market |url=https://g1.globo.com/pop-arte/musica/noticia/2019/07/30/pabllo-vittar-estreia-em-ingles-com-charli-xcx-foca-no-mercado-internacional-mas-perde-brasilidade.ghtml |website=[[G1 (website)|G1]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=Portugese |date=30 July 2019}}</ref> It features a \"percussive, [[Electronic music|electronic]]-tinged chorus\",<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kaye |first1=Ben |title=Charli XCX teams with Pabllo Vittar for \"Flash Pose\": Stream |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/07/charli-xcx-pabllo-vittar-flash-pose-stream/ |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=26 July 2019}}</ref> \"driving\" beats<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nied |first1=Mike |title=Yes, Girl! Charli XCX Links Up With Pabllo Vittar On \"Flash Pose\" |url=https://www.idolator.com/7839187/yes-girl-charli-xcx-links-up-with-pabllo-vittar-on-flash-pose?view-all |website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=25 July 2019}}</ref> and \"a roiling verse about wearing vintage Versace and party-hopping in a bright pink car ''a la'' Malibu Barbie\" by Charli XCX.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pulgar |first1=E.R. |title=Drag Superstar Pabllo Vittar Celebrates Life on Trilingual New EP, '111 1' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/pabllo-vittar-brazil-drag-new-ep-1111-919837/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=4 December 2019}}</ref> Tha\u00eds Matos of Brazilian website [[G1 (website)|G1]] noted the absence of the [[tecnobrega]] or [[Funk carioca|funk]] sound Vittar's previous releases incorporated.<ref name=\"G1\"/>\n\n== Music video ==\nThe \"Flash Pose\" music video premiered one day after the song on the [[Grindr]] app, and later, on [[YouTube]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Faia |first1=Amanda |title=Pabllo Vittar and Charli XCX release video for \"Flash Pose\" |url=https://portalpopline.com.br/pabllo-vittar-e-charli-xcx-lancam-clipe-para-flash-pose/ |website=POPline |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=Portugese |date=26 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Pabllo Vittar |title=Pabllo Vittar ft. Charli XCX - Flash Pose (Official Music Video) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rZVhR399IoA |website=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=26 July 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\nMike Wass of [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] called the song a highlight on its parent album.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wass |first1=Mike |title=Stream: Pabllo Vittar's '111' Album Is Jam-Packed With Bangers |url=https://www.idolator.com/7908473/stream-pabllo-vittars-111-album-is-jam-packed-with-bangers?view-all |website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>  Suzy Exposito of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' placed the music video on a list of the 10 best Latin music videos of July.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Exposito |first1=Suzy |title=Play It Again: The 10 Best Latin Music Videos of July |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/july-latin-music-videos-anuel-aa-residente-pabllo-vittar-865695/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=31 July 2019}}</ref> Alex Blynn praised the single, writing \"The track feels eminently danceable, fun as hell and offer[ing] a new take on classic Pabllo-sounds\".<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n\n== Release history 