hiv Mahima]]''\n|[[Lord Shiva]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1993\n|''[[Govinda Govinda]]''\n|[[Venkateswara|Lord Venkateswara]]\n|Telugu film\n|-\n|''[[Muqabla (1993 film)|Muqabla]]''\n|Havaldar Satyaprakash\n|\n|-\n|[[Bollywood films of 1994|1994]]\n|''[[Kanoon]]''\n|Pankaj\n|Vishal's brother\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Bollywood films of 1995|1995]]\n|''[[Shanivrat Mahima]]''\n|[[Indra|Bhagwan Indra]]/<br>[[Venkateswara|Lord Venkestwara]]\n|\n|-\n|''[[Haathkadi (1995 film)|Hathkadi]]''\n|Arun Chauhan\n|\n|-\n|''[[Buk Bhara Bhalobasha]]''\n|Soumitra Dutt\n|Bengali film\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Great Robbery]]''\n|[[Venkateswara|Lord Venkateswara]]\n|Telugu film\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Bollywood films of 1997|1997]]\n|''[[Dhaal: The Battle of Law Against Law]]''\n|Inspector Deodhar\n|\n|-\n|''[[Do Ankhen Barah Hath]]''\n|\n|\n|-\n|''[[Lav Kush (film)|Lav Kush]]''\n|[[Laxmana]]\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n|''[[Babul Pyaare]]''\n|Pandit Hari Singh\n|Bhojpuri Film\n|}\n\n===Television===\n*''[[Vikram Aur Betaal]]'' as King Vikramaditya\n*''[[Ramayan (1987 TV series)|Ramayan]]'' (1986\u201387) as Shri Ram\n*''[[Luv Kush]]'' (1989) as Shri Ram\n*''[[Kaise Kahoon]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Basera (Zee TV series)|Basera]]'' (2000)\n*''[[Ehsaas|Ehsaas - Kahani Ek Ghar Ki]]''\n*''[[Mashal (Doordarshan television serial)|Mashaal (Doordarshan television serial)]]'' as Ajay\n*''[[Phoolwanti (TV Series)|Phoolwanti]]'' (1992) as Pandit Vankatesh Shastri\n*''Buddha'' (1996 Sony TV) as Buddha\n*''Aparajita'' (DD National)\n*''Massian di Raat'' (Punjabi) (DD National)\n*''Jai Veer Hanuman''\n*''Karawaas''\n*''Zindagi Navrang Hai''\n*''Mrityunjay''\n*''[[Aashiqui]]'' (1998\u20131999)\n*''[[Pal Chhin]]'' (1999\u20132000) as Pratap Singh\n*''Sanjhi'' (2002 Zee TV)\n*''Supriya'' (Sab TV)\n*''Antaraal'' (DD)\n*''Hamara Apna Ghar''\n*''Gayatri Mahima'' (DD)\n*''Zindagi Teri Meri Kahani Hai'' (Sahara one)\n*''Jeet'' (Star plus)\n*''Antariksh'' (Star plus)\n*''Kartavya'' (Zee TV)\n*''Sarhadein''\n*''wo hue na humaare (DD)'' as Ravindra Damaniya\n*''Vividha'' (DD)\n*''Vishwamitra'' (DD)   as Raja Harischandra\n*''Pyar Ki Kashti Me'' (Star One\nBuddha(TV series)\n{{Expand list|date=October 2009}}\n*''harishchandra''\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of Indian television actors]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|4468244|Arun Govil}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Govil, Arun}}\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Bengali cinema]]\n[[Category:Indian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:People from Meerut]]\n[[Category:Chaudhary Charan Singh University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "106.193.107.60", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arun_Govil"}
{"title_page": "Golden Horseshoe", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|official_name          = Golden Horseshoe\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = [[Urban area]] and [[conurbation]]\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          = [[file:Toronto (15085972212).jpg|300px]]\n|image_caption          = [[Toronto]], the [[List of the 100 largest municipalities in Canada by population|most populous city in Canada]] and the country's [[financial centre]], is the anchor of the Golden Horseshoe.\n|image_map              = Map of Ontario GOLDEN HORSESHOE.svg\n|mapsize                = 250px\n|map_caption            = Location of the Golden Horseshoe in Ontario.<br /><span style=\"color:#F07568;\">\u2588\u2588</span> Core area <span style=\"color:#9BCB65;\">\u2588\u2588</span> Greater Golden Horseshoe\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = Canada\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Canada|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Ontario]]\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude         = \n|unit_pref                = <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = 10097.45\n|area_total_sq_mi         =\n|area_blank1_title        = Extended area\n|area_blank1_km2          = 21464.12\n|area_blank1_sq_mi        =\n|area_blank2_title        = Combined\n|area_blank2_km2          = 31561.57\n|area_blank2_sq_mi        = \n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of               = [[2016 Canadian Census|2016]]<!-- Do not change until the 2021 census is released -->\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                = \n|population_total               = 7,826,367<!-- Do not change until the 2021 census is released -->\n|population_density_km2         = 775.11<!-- Do not change until the 2021 census is released -->\n|population_blank1_title        = Extended area\n|population_blank1              = 1843117<!-- Do not change until the 2021 census is released -->\n|population_blank2_title        = Combined\n|population_blank2              = 9245438<!-- Do not change until the 2021 census is released -->\n\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|utc_offset             = \u22125\n|timezone_DST           = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST         = \u22124\n|coordinates            = {{coord|43.6|-79.73|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type       = Postal code prefixes\n|postal_code            = [[List of postal codes of Canada: K|K]], [[List of postal codes of Canada: L|L]], [[List of postal codes of Canada: M|M]], [[List of postal codes of Canada: N|N]]\n|area_code              = [[Area code 226|226]], [[Area code 249|249]], [[Area code 289|289]], [[Area code 365|365]], [[Area code 416|416]], [[Area code 437|437]], [[Area code 519|519]], [[Area code 548|548]], [[Area code 647|647]], [[Area code 705|705]], [[Area code 905|905]]\n}}\nThe '''Golden Horseshoe''' is a secondary region of [[Southern Ontario|Southern]] [[Ontario]], [[Canada]], which lies at the western end of [[Lake Ontario]], with outer boundaries stretching south to [[Lake Erie]] and north to [[Lake Scugog]] and [[Lake Simcoe]]. It includes the [[Greater Toronto Area]]. The region is the most densely populated and [[Industrialisation|industrialized]] in Canada. With a population of 7,826,367 people in its core and 9,245,438 in its greater area,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/91-214-x/2017000/tbl/tbl1-1-eng.htm|title=Table 1.1Population and demographic factors of growth by census metropolitan area, Canada|last=Canada|first=Government of Canada, Statistics|website=www.statcan.gc.ca|language=en|access-date=2018-01-30}}</ref> the Golden Horseshoe accounts for over 21 per cent of the population of Canada and more than 55 per cent of Ontario's population.<ref name=\"2006CensGGH\">{{cite web|url=http://geodepot.statcan.gc.ca/Diss/Maps/ThematicMaps/regional_horseshoe_e.cfm|title=Portrait of the Canadian Population in 2006: Subprovincial population dynamics, Greater Golden Horseshoe|date=2007-03-13|work=[[Statistics Canada]], 2006 Census of Population|accessdate=2007-03-13}}</ref> It is part of the [[Quebec City\u2013Windsor Corridor]] and the [[Great Lakes Megalopolis]].\n\nThe core of the Golden Horseshoe starts from [[Niagara Falls, Ontario|Niagara Falls]] at the eastern end of the [[Niagara Peninsula]] and extends west, wrapping around the western end of Lake Ontario at [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] and then turning northeast to [[Toronto]] (on the northwestern shore of Lake Ontario), before finally terminating at [[Oshawa]]. The term '''Greater Golden Horseshoe''' is used to describe a broader region that stretches inland from the core to the area of the [[Trent\u2013Severn Waterway]], such as [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]], in the northeast, to Barrie and Lake Simcoe in the north, and to the [[Grand River (Ontario)|Grand River]] area, including centres such as [[Brantford]], [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo|Waterloo Region]], and [[Guelph]] to the west. The extended region's area covers approximately {{convert|33500|km2|mi2|sigfig=2|abbr=on}}, out of this, {{convert|7300|km2|mi2|sigfig=2|abbr=on}} or approximately 22 per cent of the area is covered by the environmentally protected [[Greenbelt (Golden Horseshoe)|Greenbelt]]. The Greater Golden Horseshoe forms the neck of the [[Ontario Peninsula]]<!--please do not remove without consensus-->.\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:Golden Horseshoe snowily wrapping the end of Lake Ontario.jpeg|thumb|left|The western end of [[Lake Ontario]]. The region takes its name from the horseshoe shape formed from the [[Burlington Heights (Ontario)|Burlington Heights]].]]\nThe ''horseshoe'' part of the region's name is derived from the characteristic [[horseshoe]] shape of the west end of Lake Ontario with [[Cootes Paradise]] between [[Burlington, Ontario|Burlington]] and [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] roughly positioned in the centre. The ''golden'' part is historically attributed to the region's wealth and prosperity, according to the ''[[Canadian Oxford Dictionary]]''.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |editor-last=Barber |editor-first=Katherine |editor-link= |encyclopedia=Canadian Oxford Dictionary |title=Golden Horseshoe |url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780195418163.001.0001/m_en_ca0028885 |access-date= 11 September 2017 |edition=2nd |year=2005 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn= 9780195418163 |quote=ORIGIN: So called with reference to the area's wealth and horseshoe-like shape.}}</ref>\n\nThe phrase ''Golden Horseshoe'' was first used by [[Westinghouse Electric Corporation]] president Herbert H. Rogge in a speech to the Hamilton Chamber of Commerce on January 12, 1954:\n\n{{quote|text=Hamilton in 50 years will be the forward cleat in a \"golden horseshoe\" of industrial development from Oshawa to the Niagara River&nbsp;... {{convert|150|mi|km|disp=sqbr}} long and {{convert|50|mi|km|disp=sqbr}} wide&nbsp;... It will run from Niagara Falls on the south to about Oshawa on the north and take in numerous cities and towns already there, including Hamilton and Toronto.<ref name=Bank>{{cite web|title=Fast Facts from Hamilton's Past |url=http://www.myhamilton.ca/myhamilton/LibraryServices/Localhistory/Fast+Facts.htm |accessdate=2007-01-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060905060213/http://www.myhamilton.ca/myhamilton/LibraryServices/Localhistory/Fast+Facts.htm |archivedate=2006-09-05 }}</ref>}}\n\nThe speech writer who actually penned the phrase was Charles Hunter MacBain, executive assistant to five Westinghouse presidents including Rogge.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Strada|first1=Eric|title=Looking Back: The Golden Truth|url=http://www.bizmagazine.ca/sitepages/?aid=3623&cn=LOOKING%20BACK&an=The%20Golden%20Truth%20%7C%20Q1%202011|website=Biz Magazine|publisher=Postmedia Network|accessdate=September 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Definition==\nThe Golden Horseshoe has been recognised as a geographic region since the 1950s, but it was only on July 13, 2004, that a report from the provincial Ministry of Public Infrastructure Renewal entitled ''Places to Grow'' coined the term ''Greater Golden Horseshoe'', extending the boundaries west to [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo|Waterloo Region]], north to [[Barrie]]/[[Simcoe County]], and northeast to the [[Peterborough County|county]] and city of [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pir.gov.on.ca/userfiles/HTML/cma_4_35657_1.html |title=Places to Grow |accessdate=2006-09-13 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060907081829/http://www.pir.gov.on.ca/userfiles/HTML/cma_4_35657_1.html |archivedate=2006-09-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  A subsequent edition released February 16, 2005, broadened the term further, adding [[County of Brant|Brant]], [[Haldimand County|Haldimand]] and [[Northumberland County, Ontario|Northumberland]] Counties to the now quasi-administrative region. The Greater Golden Horseshoe region is officially designated in Ontario Regulation 416/05<ref>{{cite web |title=Places to Grow Act, 2005 - Ontario Regulation 416/05 - Growth Plan Areas |url=https://www.ontario.ca/laws/regulation/050416 |publisher=Government of Ontario |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> under the ''[http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05p13_e.htm Places to Grow Act]''. The designation Greater Golden Horseshoe has legal significance with respect to taxation: in April 2017, the Government of Ontario announced plans to impose a 15 per cent Non-Resident Speculation Tax (NRST) on non-Canadian citizens, non-permanent residents and non-Canadian corporations (with exceptions or rebates for refugees, qualifying students and certain people working in Ontario<ref>{{cite web|title=Ontario slaps 15% tax on foreign buyers, expands rent control in 16-point plan to cool housing|last1=Marr|first1=Garry|url=http://business.financialpost.com/personal-finance/mortgages-real-estate/ontario-slaps-15-tax-on-foreign-buyers-expands-rent-control-in-16-point-plan-to-cool-housing|publisher=Financial Post|accessdate=30 April 2017}}</ref>) buying residential properties containing one to six units in the Greater Golden Horseshoe (GGH).<ref>{{cite web|author1=Office of the Premier|title=News Release:  Making Housing More Affordable|url=https://news.ontario.ca/opo/en/2017/04/making-housing-more-affordable.html|publisher=Queen's Printer for Ontario|accessdate=30 April 2017|date=April 20, 2017|quote=introducing a 15 per cent Non-Resident Speculation Tax (NRST) on non-Canadian citizens, non-permanent residents and non-Canadian corporations buying residential properties containing one to six units in the Greater Golden Horseshoe (GGH).}}</ref>\n\nThe provincial transit authority [[Metrolinx]] makes use of the term Greater Golden Horseshoe. The Metrolinx definition is consistent with the original 2004 ''Places to Grow'' definition. However, the city and county of Peterborough is not included.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metrolinx.com/en/greaterregion/Default.aspx|title=For a Greater Region|agency=Metrolinx|accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nThe population of the Golden Horseshoe was 7.82 million residents at the 2016 census. The region is projected to grow to 11.5 million people by 2031.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.york.ca/NR/rdonlyres/kmqilaodjh2lz6ragkdgdkqhrsloj4oq4moz2gsf6igbts37ovmqpzih6dkbo2vaiujmnkmd6ritcxidjf3x36os2d/%28Growth+Management%29+Presentation+-+GTAH+Forecast.pdf |title=Greater Golden Horseshoe, GTA and Hamilton Population, Household and Employment Forecasts |date=February 2005 |publisher=Regional Municipality of York|archive-date=July 6, 2011 |archive-url=http://www.york.ca/NR/rdonlyres/kmqilaodjh2lz6ragkdgdkqhrsloj4oq4moz2gsf6igbts37ovmqpzih6dkbo2vaiujmnkmd6ritcxidjf3x36os2d/(Growth+Management)+Presentation+-+GTAH+Forecast.pdf}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Ethnic groups in the Greater Golden Horseshoe\n! [[Ethnic group]] !! Population !! %\n|-\n| [[European Canadian|European]] || 5,088,240|| {{Percentage | 5088240| 9083158| 1}}\n|- \n| [[South Asian Canadians|South Asian]] || 1,068,520|| {{Percentage | 1068520| 9083158| 1}}\n|-\n| [[East Asian]] || 787,365|| {{Percentage | 787365|9083158| 1}}\n|- \n| [[African-Canadian|African]] || 523,230|| {{Percentage | 523230| 9083158| 1}}\n|-\n| [[Southeast Asian]] || 391,870|| {{Percentage | 391870| 9083158| 1}}\n|-\n| [[Arab Canadians|Middle Eastern]] || 271,595|| {{Percentage | 271595| 9083158| 1}}\n|-\n| [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Aboriginal]] || 198,140|| {{Percentage | 198140| 9083158| 1}}\n|-\n| [[Latin American Canadians|Latin American]] || 165,700|| {{Percentage | 165700| 9083158| 1}}\n|-\n| Other || 202,945|| {{Percentage | 202945| 9083158| 1}}\n|- style=\"background:#efefef; font-weight:bold\"\n| Total population (2016) || 9,245,438|| {{Percentage | 9245438| 9245438| 1}}\n|}\n{{smalldiv|1=Source:<ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3514&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Northumberland&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3515&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Peterborough&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3543&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Simcoe&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3523&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Wellington&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3522&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Dufferin&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3518&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Durham&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3524&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Halton&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3526&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Niagara&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3520005&Geo2=CD&Code2=3520&Data=Count&SearchText=Toronto&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3530&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Waterloo&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3525005&Geo2=CD&Code2=3525&Data=Count&SearchText=Hamilton&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3528018&Geo2=CD&Code2=3528&Data=Count&SearchText=Haldimand&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3516010&Geo2=CD&Code2=3516&Data=Count&SearchText=Kawartha&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3529005&Geo2=CD&Code2=3529&Data=Count&SearchText=Brant&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3521&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Peel&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3519&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=York&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref>}}\n\n==Economy==\n{{Main|Economy of Toronto|Economy of Hamilton, Ontario}}\n{{update|section|date=July 2012}}\nThe economy of this region is very diverse. The [[Toronto Stock Exchange]] is the third largest in North America by market capitalization (after the [[New York Stock Exchange]] and [[Nasdaq]]), and seventh largest in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2ontario.com/welcome/bcfs_400.asp |title=Toronto Stock Exchange is the Third Largest in North America |website=2Ontario.com  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211113516/http://www.2ontario.com/welcome/bcfs_400.asp |archive-date=February 11, 2007}}</ref> \n[[File:Oakville Assembly.jpg|thumb|left|A worker installing car batteries at Ford's [[Oakville Assembly]]. The automotive industry is a major sector of the Golden Horseshoe's economy.]]\nCities including Hamilton, Oshawa, Oakville, Whitby and Kitchener all contain major large-scale industrial production facilities, Hamilton being dominated by the [[Steel#Steel industry|steel industry]] and Oakville and Oshawa primarily in the [[automotive industry]]. Other significant automotive-production facilities also exist in [[Brampton]], and [[St. Catharines]]. While manufacturing remains important to the economy of the region, the manufacturing sector has experienced a significant decline since 2000 as a result of unfavourable currency exchange rates, increasing energy costs, and reduced demand from the United States, which is by far the largest market for Ontario's goods.\n\nThe [[Hamilton-Oshawa Port Authority|Port of Hamilton]] and the [[PortsToronto|Port of Toronto]] are the two largest [[Port#Seaport|seaports]] on [[Lake Ontario]]. The [[Welland Canal]] system handles tanker ship and recreational traffic through the Great Lakes. Large rail and truck distribution facilities are located in Toronto, [[Vaughan]] and Brampton. Food processing is also a key ingredient in the economy. \n[[File:Wine grapes nearing harvest in Ontario-also example of trellis wire.jpg|thumb|The [[Niagara Peninsula]] is Canada's largest wine growing region and a major producer of [[Ontario wine]].]]\nNiagara Falls has one of the world's largest per-capita tourist economies, benefiting from millions of tourists coming to see its majestic waterfalls, shop in its numerous stores, and visit its many attractions. The winemaking and fruit growing industries of the [[Niagara Peninsula]] produce award-winning wines, which are beginning to attract attention around the world, in particular the [[ice wine]] for which the region is known.\n\nAs of 2014, sectors such as [[information technology]], health care, tourism, research and finance provide the bulk of growth in the Golden Horseshoe. The suburban cities within [[Greater Toronto]], such as [[Brampton]], [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], and [[Mississauga]], are emerging as hubs for technology and innovation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brampton.ca/EN/Business/economic-development/Key-Sectors/Pages/Innovation-and-Technology.aspx|title=Innovation & Technology|website=www.brampton.ca}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nThe Golden Horseshoe is home to several [[university|universities]], including the [[University of Toronto]] and [[McMaster University]] in Hamilton, which are ranked 1st and 4th in Canada, respectively, by the [[Academic Ranking of World Universities]]. Other universities in the region include [[Brock University]] in St. Catherines, [[Trent University]] in Peterborough, [[York University]], [[OCAD University]], [[University of Ontario Institute of Technology]] in Oshawa, [[Ryerson University]], [[University of Guelph]], [[University of Waterloo]], [[Wilfrid Laurier University]] in Waterloo, and [[Universit\u00e9 de l'Ontario fran\u00e7ais]].\n\nPublic primary and secondary schooling is typically provided by [[school boards]], largely organized at the municipal or county/regional level. The only school board that operates throughout the Golden Horseshoe is [[Conseil scolaire Viamonde]], a public French-language school board, and [[Conseil scolaire catholique MonAvenir]], a public French-language [[separate school|separate]] school board. Both of these public French-language school boards operate across the Ontario Peninsula.\n\n==Attractions==\n{{See also|Attractions in Toronto}}\n[[File:Caribana 2009 (2).jpg|thumb|[[Toronto Caribbean Carnival]] is an annual cultural festival held in the City of Toronto.]]\nFormerly the [[List of tallest freestanding structures|tallest freestanding structure on land in the world]], the [[CN Tower]] in Toronto is among the most internationally notable attractions in the Golden Horseshoe.\n\nThe city is home to several [[shopping mall]]s such as [[Yorkdale Shopping Centre]], [[Toronto Eaton Centre]] (which is North America's busiest shopping mall),<ref>{{cite web|title=Canadian Shopping Centre Study|url=http://www.retailcouncil.org/sites/default/files/RCCCanadianShoppingCenterStudyFINAL.pdf|publisher=[[Retail Council of Canada]]|accessdate=18 January 2017|date=December 2016}}</ref> [[Scarborough Town Centre]], and [[Sherway Gardens]]. Located in the suburbs of Toronto are [[Vaughan Mills]] in [[Vaughan]], [[Bramalea City Centre]] in [[Brampton]] and [[Square One Shopping Centre]] in [[Mississauga]], the largest shopping mall in Ontario. [[Pacific Mall]], in [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], is the largest ethnic shopping mall in eastern Canada.\n\nAnnual cultural festivals that draw tourists and local alike include the Peeks Caribbean Carnival (formerly known as [[Caribana]]) and [[Taste of the Danforth]] in Toronto.\n[[File:Webster Falls - Laslovarga1.jpg|thumb|left|View of [[Webster's Falls]] in Hamilton. The falls is a part of the [[Niagara Escarpment Biosphere Reserve]], which runs across the western portion of the Golden Horseshoe.]]\nThe [[Niagara Escarpment]], a world biosphere as designated by the United Nations, runs from the north at Bruce Peninsula and then east through the region cutting the Niagara Gorge at Niagara Falls. The [[Bruce Trail]] runs along the escarpment through mostly protected woodlands. The [[Cheltenham Badlands]] in Caledon is an [[Environmental degradation|environmentally degraded]] area along the Niagara Escarpment. Similar protection of some wooded areas exists on the [[Oak Ridges Moraine]] running east\u2013west in the north end of the Greater Toronto Area, although development pressures continue to threaten the natural habitat.\n\nThe Niagara Region has become one of the major [[wine]]-production areas in Canada. The Golden Horseshoe contains many small towns with tourist-jammed, historic main streets, most notably the community of [[Niagara-on-the-Lake]], located at the mouth of the [[Niagara River]]. [[Niagara Falls, Ontario|Niagara Falls]] is one of the world's largest waterfalls, and attracts millions to [[Clifton Hill, Niagara Falls|Clifton Hill]], a neighbourhood featuring hundreds of amusements, souvenir stores, restaurants and skyline-changing hotels. Casinos here are also a huge draw.\n\n[[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] has the historical reputation of being a blue-collar city; however, waterfront redevelopments and large-scale [[gentrification]] have been rapidly changing the perception of the city, although it retains a dominant industrial base. Hamilton has over [[List of waterfalls in Hamilton, Ontario|100 waterfalls]] and cascades throughout the region.\n[[File:Leviathan Lift and Sculpture.jpg|thumb|View of [[Leviathan (roller coaster)|the Leviathan roller coaster]] at [[Canada's Wonderland]]. Located in [[Vaughan]], Wonderland is Canada's largest and most attended amusement park.]]\nThere are a number of [[Amusement park|theme parks]] in the Golden Horseshoe, all of which are seasonal. [[Canada's Wonderland]], run by [[Cedar Fair]] in Vaughan, {{convert|2|km|mi|abbr=on}} north of Vaughan Mills, is the largest and most attended theme park in Canada, as well as the most attended seasonal theme park in North America. Other theme parks include [[Wet'n'Wild Toronto]] (formerly Wild Water Kingdom) in [[Brampton]], [[African Lion Safari]] in [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] and [[Cambridge, Ontario|Cambridge]], and [[Marineland of Canada|Marineland]] in Niagara Falls.  Though not a theme park per se, the [[Exhibition Place]] hosts the annual [[Canadian National Exhibition]], which is Canada's largest annual fair.\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Toronto vs Tampa Aug 11 2018.jpg|thumb|right|A [[Toronto Blue Jays]] game at the [[Rogers Centre]] in 2018]]\nThe Golden Horseshoe is home to many professional sports teams, most of which are Toronto-based. These teams include:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Team\n!City\n!League\n!Sport\n|-\n|[[Toronto Blue Jays]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[Major League Baseball|MLB]]\n|Baseball\n|-\n|[[Toronto Raptors]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n|Basketball\n|-\n|[[Raptors 905]]\n|[[Mississauga]]\n|[[NBA G League|G League]]\n|Basketball\n|-\n|[[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]]\n|[[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]]\n|[[Canadian Football League|CFL]]\n|Canadian Football\n|-\n|[[Toronto Argonauts]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[Canadian Football League|CFL]]\n|Canadian Football\n|-\n|[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n|Ice Hockey\n|-\n|[[Toronto Marlies]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n|Ice Hockey\n|-\n|[[Toronto Rock]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[National Lacrosse League|NLL]]\n|Indoor Lacrosse\n|-\n|[[Toronto Wolfpack]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[RFL Championship|Championship]]\n|Rugby League\n|-\n|[[Toronto FC]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[Major League Soccer|MLS]]\n|Soccer\n|-\n|[[Toronto FC II]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[USL League One]]\n|Soccer\n|-\n|[[Forge FC]]\n|[[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]]\n|[[Canadian Premier League|CPL]]\n|Soccer\n|-\n|[[York 9 FC|York9 FC]]\n|[[Vaughan]]\n|[[Canadian Premier League|CPL]]\n|Soccer\n|}\nThe Golden Horseshoe hosted the [[2015 Pan American Games]] and the [[2015 Parapan American Games]].\n\nUniversities' athletic teams in the Golden Horseshoe belong to [[U Sports]].\n\n==Transportation==\n{{see also|Transportation in Toronto}}\n[[File:QEW into Mississauga.png|thumb|The [[Queen Elizabeth Way]] is a major [[controlled-access highway]] that connects Greater Toronto with the Niagara Peninsula.]]\nThe Golden Horseshoe is served by an [[400-series highways|extensive network of expressways]], the backbone of which are the [[Queen Elizabeth Way]] and [[Ontario Highway 401|Highway 401]], one of the widest and busiest expressways in the world. Public transit in the region is coordinated by [[Metrolinx]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metrolinx.com/en/aboutus/about_us_index.aspx|title=About Us|agency=Metrolinx|accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref> Regional transit is provided by [[GO Transit]] trains and buses, and by private bus operators Greyhound and Coach Canada. Local transit is provided by municipal agencies, the largest of which is the [[Toronto Transit Commission]], which operates [[Toronto subway|three subway lines and one light metro line]] and an extensive [[Toronto Transit Commission bus system|bus]] and [[Toronto streetcar system|streetcar network]]. Toronto is currently the only city in the area with a rail-based local transit network, though its subway system extends to Vaughan as well at [[Vaughan Metropolitan Centre station]] since December 2017. However, several cities in the region have light rail lines in the works.<ref name=\"Kitchener LRT\">{{cite news|last=Outhit|first=Jeff|title=Rail yard purchased for rapid transit|url=http://www.therecord.com/news/local/article/615558--rail-yard-purchased-for-rapid-transit|accessdate=2012-04-08|newspaper=Waterloo Region Record|date=Oct 27, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Hurontario\">{{cite web|url=http://hurontario-main.ca/PDFs/masterplan/Hurontario_Master_Plan_Final_HighRes.pdf|publisher=MMM Group|title=Hurontario/Main Street Corridor Master Plan|page=578|date=October 2010|format=PDF|accessdate=2012-04-08|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324044621/http://hurontario-main.ca/PDFs/masterplan/Hurontario_Master_Plan_Final_HighRes.pdf|archivedate=2012-03-24}}</ref> These include the approved [[Hurontario LRT]] in [[Regional Municipality of Peel|Peel Region]] and [[B-Line (Hamilton)|B-Line]] in [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]].\n\nThe primary airport of the region is [[Toronto Pearson International Airport]] (officially Lester B. Pearson International Airport), located in Mississauga, which is the busiest in Canada and the [[List of busiest airports by passenger traffic|31st busiest in the world]], handling over 49.5 million passengers in 2018, and offering non-stop flights worldwide where it ranks [[List of busiest airports by aircraft movements|13th in the world]]. Other regional airports of significance include [[John C. Munro Hamilton International Airport]] located in southern Hamilton, which is a major regional freight and courier location as well as the [[Region of Waterloo International Airport]] in Kitchener; [[Buttonville Municipal Airport|Buttonville Airport]] and [[Billy Bishop Toronto City Airport|Billy Bishop airport]] in the [[Greater Toronto Area]], both of which mostly serve regional business travellers but the latter being the third largest in the region for passenger volume. Within driving distance is [[Buffalo Niagara International Airport]] in [[Cheektowaga, New York]], in the United States. Buffalo Niagara carries the second largest passenger volume in the region, serving over 5 million passengers in 2018.<ref>https://www.wgrz.com/article/travel/bnia-celebrates-major-milestone/71-63d09d28-eb5f-454a-952b-ff4ff4ff7a61</ref> It is frequently used by Canadian passengers flying to US destinations.\n\n==Divisions==\n{{see also|Greater Toronto and Hamilton Area}}\n[[File:Downtown Toronto in September 2018 (Early Sunday Morning, view from a kayak).jpg|right|thumb|alt=A spear-like tower is between a white-domed structure and small buildings on the left, and increasingly taller buildings to the right. In the foreground is a lake, with a few visible buoys, and the background is a deep blue sky with a few clouds near the horizon.|Skyline of [[Downtown Toronto]]. The city is the financial anchor of the Golden Horseshoe.]]\n[[Image:HamiltonOntarioSkylineC.JPG|right|thumb|alt=A tree-lined highway is in the foreground, angled diagonally from bottom right to middle left of the image. Buildings are in the centre, and the background is a sky meeting rolling hills in the distance.|[[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] lies at the western edge of [[Lake Ontario]].]]\n[[File:Cataratas del Ni\u00e1gara 31.jpg|thumb|alt=A spike tower with a pod is lit along its length on the right. Other buildings sit on the right while a river and large waterfall occupies the left.|[[Niagara Falls, Ontario|Niagara Falls]] is a major tourist destination, situated at the southern portion of the Golden Horseshoe.]]\n\n===Municipalities===\n{{see also|List of municipalities in the Greater Toronto Area}}\n<!-- populations come from each article, which in turn come from the 2016 Census -->\n<!-- list of municipalities comes from here: http://placestogrow.ca/index.php?Itemid=14&id=430&option=com_content&task=view -->\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Section\n! Census division\n! Population\n|-\n| Core || [[Regional Municipality of Durham|Durham Region]] || 645,862\n|-\n| Core || [[Regional Municipality of Halton|Halton Region]] || 548,435\n|-\n| Core || [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] || 536,917\n|-\n| Core || [[Regional Municipality of Niagara|Niagara Region]] || 447,888\n|-\n| Core || [[Regional Municipality of Peel|Peel Region]] || 1,381,739\n|-\n| Core || [[Toronto]] || 2,731,571\n|-\n| Core || [[Regional Municipality of York|York Region]] || 1,109,909\n|-\n| Core \n|data-sort-value=\"zzzz\"| ''Total core'' || ''7,402,321''\n|-\n| Extended || Brant ([[County of Brant]] and [[Brantford]]) ||134,808\n|-\n| Extended || [[Dufferin County]] || 61,735\n|-\n| Extended || [[Haldimand County]] || \t44,876\n|-\n| Extended || [[Kawartha Lakes]] || 75,423\n|-\n| Extended || [[Northumberland County, Ontario|Northumberland County]] || 85,598\n|-\n| Extended || Peterborough ([[Peterborough County]] and the city of [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]])|| 138,236\n|-\n| Extended || Simcoe ([[Simcoe County]], [[Barrie]] and [[Orillia]]) || 479,650\n|-\n| Extended || [[Waterloo Region]] || 535,154\n|-\n| Extended || Wellington ([[Wellington County, Ontario|Wellington County]] and [[Guelph]]) || 222,726\n|-\n|-\n| Extended\n| data-sort-value=\"zzzy\"| ''Total extended'' || ''1,778,206''\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"zzzz\"| '''Total''' ||'''all''' || '''9,180,527'''\n|}\n\n===Census metropolitan areas===\nPopulation figures are from the 2016 census.\n\nThe [[census metropolitan area]]s listed below are within the Greater Golden Horseshoe. Not all land within the Greater Golden Horseshoe is part of a Census Metropolitan Area; some Census Metropolitan Areas are partly in the Golden Horseshoe and partly outside it.\n\n# [[Toronto]] 5,928,040<!--Peel and York Regions are completely within Toronto CMA-->\n# [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] 747,545\n# [[St. Catharines]]-[[Regional Municipality of Niagara|Niagara]] 406,074\n# [[Oshawa]] 379,848\n# [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]]-[[Cambridge, Ontario|Cambridge]]-[[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]] 523,894\n# [[Barrie]] 197,059\n# [[Guelph]] 151,984\n# [[Brantford]] 134,203\n# [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]] 121,721\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{wikivoyage-inline|Golden Horseshoe}}\n*[https://www.cityofwaterfalls.ca/ The City Of Waterfalls]\n*\n\n{{Subdivisions of Ontario}}\n{{Canadian City Geographic Location (8-way)\n | Northwest = [[Georgian Triangle]]\n | North = [[Central Ontario]]\n | Northeast = [[Central Ontario]] / [[Eastern Ontario]]\n | West = [[Southwestern Ontario]]\n | Centre = Golden Horseshoe\n | East = [[Eastern Ontario]] / [[Western New York]]\n | Southwest = [[Southwestern Ontario]]\n | South = [[Upstate New York]] / [[Niagara Frontier]]\n | Southeast = ''[[Lake Ontario]]'' / [[Finger Lakes]]\n | image = \n}}\n{{Portal bar|Ontario|Canada}}\n\n[[Category:Metropolitan areas of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Geographic regions of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Golden Horseshoe| ]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1950s]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|official_name          = Golden Horseshoe\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = [[Urban area]] and [[conurbation]]\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          = [[file:Toronto (15085972212).jpg|300px]]\n|image_caption          = [[Toronto]], the [[List of the 100 largest municipalities in Canada by population|most populous city in Canada]] and the country's [[financial centre]], is the anchor of the Golden Horseshoe.\n|image_map              = Map of Ontario GOLDEN HORSESHOE.svg\n|mapsize                = 250px\n|map_caption            = Location of the Golden Horseshoe in Ontario.<br /><span style=\"color:#F07568;\">\u2588\u2588</span> Core area <span style=\"color:#9BCB65;\">\u2588\u2588</span> Greater Golden Horseshoe\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = Canada\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Canada|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Ontario]]\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude         = \n|unit_pref                = <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = 10097.45\n|area_total_sq_mi         =\n|area_blank1_title        = Extended area\n|area_blank1_km2          = 21464.12\n|area_blank1_sq_mi        =\n|area_blank2_title        = Combined\n|area_blank2_km2          = 31561.57\n|area_blank2_sq_mi        = \n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of               = [[2016 Canadian Census|2016]]<!-- Do not change until the 2021 census is released -->\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                = \n|population_total               = 7,826,367<!-- Do not change until the 2021 census is released -->\n|population_density_km2         = 775.11<!-- Do not change until the 2021 census is released -->\n|population_blank1_title        = Extended area\n|population_blank1              = 1843117<!-- Do not change until the 2021 census is released -->\n|population_blank2_title        = Combined\n|population_blank2              = 9245438<!-- Do not change until the 2021 census is released -->\n\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|utc_offset             = \u22125\n|timezone_DST           = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST         = \u22124\n|coordinates            = {{coord|43.6|-79.73|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type       = Postal code prefixes\n|postal_code            = [[List of postal codes of Canada: K|K]], [[List of postal codes of Canada: L|L]], [[List of postal codes of Canada: M|M]], [[List of postal codes of Canada: N|N]]\n|area_code              = [[Area code 226|226]], [[Area code 249|249]], [[Area code 289|289]], [[Area code 365|365]], [[Area code 416|416]], [[Area code 437|437]], [[Area code 519|519]], [[Area code 548|548]], [[Area code 647|647]], [[Area code 705|705]], [[Area code 905|905]]\n}}\nThe '''Golden Horseshoe''' is a secondary region of [[Southern Ontario|Southern]] [[Ontario]], [[Canada]], which lies at the western end of [[Lake Ontario]], with outer boundaries stretching south to [[Lake Erie]] and north to [[Lake Scugog]] and [[Lake Simcoe]]. It includes the [[Greater Toronto Area]]. The region is the most densely populated and [[Industrialisation|industrialized]] in Canada. With a population of 7,826,367 people in its core and 9,245,438 in its greater area,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/91-214-x/2017000/tbl/tbl1-1-eng.htm|title=Table 1.1Population and demographic factors of growth by census metropolitan area, Canada|last=Canada|first=Government of Canada, Statistics|website=www.statcan.gc.ca|language=en|access-date=2018-01-30}}</ref> the Golden Horseshoe accounts for over 21 per cent of the population of Canada and more than 55 per cent of Ontario's population.<ref name=\"2006CensGGH\">{{cite web|url=http://geodepot.statcan.gc.ca/Diss/Maps/ThematicMaps/regional_horseshoe_e.cfm|title=Portrait of the Canadian Population in 2006: Subprovincial population dynamics, Greater Golden Horseshoe|date=2007-03-13|work=[[Statistics Canada]], 2006 Census of Population|accessdate=2007-03-13}}</ref> It is part of the [[Quebec City\u2013Windsor Corridor]] and the [[Great Lakes Megalopolis]].\n\nThe core of the Golden Horseshoe starts from [[Niagara Falls, Ontario|Niagara Falls]] at the eastern end of the [[Niagara Peninsula]] and extends west, wrapping around the western end of Lake Ontario at [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] and then turning northeast to [[Toronto]] (on the northwestern shore of Lake Ontario), before finally terminating at [[Oshawa]]. The term '''Greater Golden Horseshoe''' is used to describe a broader region that stretches inland from the core to the area of the [[Trent\u2013Severn Waterway]], such as [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]], in the northeast, to Barrie and Lake Simcoe in the north, and to the [[Grand River (Ontario)|Grand River]] area, including centres such as [[Brantford]], [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo|Waterloo Region]], and [[Guelph]] to the west. The extended region's area covers approximately {{convert|33500|km2|mi2|sigfig=2|abbr=on}}, out of this, {{convert|7300|km2|mi2|sigfig=2|abbr=on}} or approximately 22 per cent of the area is covered by the environmentally protected [[Greenbelt (Golden Horseshoe)|Greenbelt]]. The Greater Golden Horseshoe forms the neck of the [[Ontario Peninsula]]<!--please do not remove without consensus-->.\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:Golden Horseshoe snowily wrapping the end of Lake Ontario.jpeg|thumb|left|The western end of [[Lake Ontario]]. The region takes its name from the horseshoe shape formed from the [[Burlington Heights (Ontario)|Burlington Heights]].]]\nThe ''horseshoe'' part of the region's name is derived from the characteristic [[horseshoe]] shape of the west end of Lake Ontario with [[Cootes Paradise]] between [[Burlington, Ontario|Burlington]] and [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] roughly positioned in the centre. The ''golden'' part is historically attributed to the region's wealth and prosperity, according to the ''[[Canadian Oxford Dictionary]]''.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |editor-last=Barber |editor-first=Katherine |editor-link= |encyclopedia=Canadian Oxford Dictionary |title=Golden Horseshoe |url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780195418163.001.0001/m_en_ca0028885 |access-date= 11 September 2017 |edition=2nd |year=2005 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn= 9780195418163 |quote=ORIGIN: So called with reference to the area's wealth and horseshoe-like shape.}}</ref>\n\nThe phrase ''Golden Horseshoe'' was first used by [[Westinghouse Electric Corporation]] president Herbert H. Rogge in a speech to the Hamilton Chamber of Commerce on January 12, 1954:\n\n{{quote|text=Hamilton in 50 years will be the forward cleat in a \"golden horseshoe\" of industrial development from Oshawa to the Niagara River&nbsp;... {{convert|150|mi|km|disp=sqbr}} long and {{convert|50|mi|km|disp=sqbr}} wide&nbsp;... It will run from Niagara Falls on the south to about Oshawa on the north and take in numerous cities and towns already there, including Hamilton and Toronto.<ref name=Bank>{{cite web|title=Fast Facts from Hamilton's Past |url=http://www.myhamilton.ca/myhamilton/LibraryServices/Localhistory/Fast+Facts.htm |accessdate=2007-01-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060905060213/http://www.myhamilton.ca/myhamilton/LibraryServices/Localhistory/Fast+Facts.htm |archivedate=2006-09-05 }}</ref>}}\n\nThe speech writer who actually penned the phrase was Charles Hunter MacBain, executive assistant to five Westinghouse presidents including Rogge.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Strada|first1=Eric|title=Looking Back: The Golden Truth|url=http://www.bizmagazine.ca/sitepages/?aid=3623&cn=LOOKING%20BACK&an=The%20Golden%20Truth%20%7C%20Q1%202011|website=Biz Magazine|publisher=Postmedia Network|accessdate=September 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Definition==\nThe Golden Horseshoe has been recognised as a geographic region since the 1950s, but it was only on July 13, 2004, that a report from the provincial Ministry of Public Infrastructure Renewal entitled ''Places to Grow'' coined the term ''Greater Golden Horseshoe'', extending the boundaries west to [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo|Waterloo Region]], north to [[Barrie]]/[[Simcoe County]], and northeast to the [[Peterborough County|county]] and city of [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pir.gov.on.ca/userfiles/HTML/cma_4_35657_1.html |title=Places to Grow |accessdate=2006-09-13 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060907081829/http://www.pir.gov.on.ca/userfiles/HTML/cma_4_35657_1.html |archivedate=2006-09-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  A subsequent edition released February 16, 2005, broadened the term further, adding [[County of Brant|Brant]], [[Haldimand County|Haldimand]] and [[Northumberland County, Ontario|Northumberland]] Counties to the now quasi-administrative region. The Greater Golden Horseshoe region is officially designated in Ontario Regulation 416/05<ref>{{cite web |title=Places to Grow Act, 2005 - Ontario Regulation 416/05 - Growth Plan Areas |url=https://www.ontario.ca/laws/regulation/050416 |publisher=Government of Ontario |accessdate=January 30, 2019}}</ref> under the ''[http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_05p13_e.htm Places to Grow Act]''. The designation Greater Golden Horseshoe has legal significance with respect to taxation: in April 2017, the Government of Ontario announced plans to impose a 15 per cent Non-Resident Speculation Tax (NRST) on non-Canadian citizens, non-permanent residents and non-Canadian corporations (with exceptions or rebates for refugees, qualifying students and certain people working in Ontario<ref>{{cite web|title=Ontario slaps 15% tax on foreign buyers, expands rent control in 16-point plan to cool housing|last1=Marr|first1=Garry|url=http://business.financialpost.com/personal-finance/mortgages-real-estate/ontario-slaps-15-tax-on-foreign-buyers-expands-rent-control-in-16-point-plan-to-cool-housing|publisher=Financial Post|accessdate=30 April 2017}}</ref>) buying residential properties containing one to six units in the Greater Golden Horseshoe (GGH).<ref>{{cite web|author1=Office of the Premier|title=News Release:  Making Housing More Affordable|url=https://news.ontario.ca/opo/en/2017/04/making-housing-more-affordable.html|publisher=Queen's Printer for Ontario|accessdate=30 April 2017|date=April 20, 2017|quote=introducing a 15 per cent Non-Resident Speculation Tax (NRST) on non-Canadian citizens, non-permanent residents and non-Canadian corporations buying residential properties containing one to six units in the Greater Golden Horseshoe (GGH).}}</ref>\n\nThe provincial transit authority [[Metrolinx]] makes use of the term Greater Golden Horseshoe. The Metrolinx definition is consistent with the original 2004 ''Places to Grow'' definition. However, the city and county of Peterborough is not included.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metrolinx.com/en/greaterregion/Default.aspx|title=For a Greater Region|agency=Metrolinx|accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nThe population of the Golden Horseshoe was 7.82 million residents at the 2016 census. The region is projected to grow to 11.5 million people by 2031.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.york.ca/NR/rdonlyres/kmqilaodjh2lz6ragkdgdkqhrsloj4oq4moz2gsf6igbts37ovmqpzih6dkbo2vaiujmnkmd6ritcxidjf3x36os2d/%28Growth+Management%29+Presentation+-+GTAH+Forecast.pdf |title=Greater Golden Horseshoe, GTA and Hamilton Population, Household and Employment Forecasts |date=February 2005 |publisher=Regional Municipality of York|archive-date=July 6, 2011 |archive-url=http://www.york.ca/NR/rdonlyres/kmqilaodjh2lz6ragkdgdkqhrsloj4oq4moz2gsf6igbts37ovmqpzih6dkbo2vaiujmnkmd6ritcxidjf3x36os2d/(Growth+Management)+Presentation+-+GTAH+Forecast.pdf}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Ethnic groups in the Greater Golden Horseshoe\n! [[Ethnic group]] !! Population !! %\n|-\n| [[European Canadian|European]] || 5,088,240|| {{Percentage | 5088240| 9083158| 1}}\n|- \n| [[South Asian Canadians|South Asian]] || 1,068,520|| {{Percentage | 1068520| 9083158| 1}}\n|-\n| [[East Asian]] || 787,365|| {{Percentage | 787365|9083158| 1}}\n|- \n| [[African-Canadian|African]] || 523,230|| {{Percentage | 523230| 9083158| 1}}\n|-\n| [[Southeast Asian]] || 391,870|| {{Percentage | 391870| 9083158| 1}}\n|-\n| [[Arab Canadians|Middle Eastern]] || 271,595|| {{Percentage | 271595| 9083158| 1}}\n|-\n| [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Aboriginal]] || 198,140|| {{Percentage | 198140| 9083158| 1}}\n|-\n| [[Latin American Canadians|Latin American]] || 165,700|| {{Percentage | 165700| 9083158| 1}}\n|-\n| Other || 202,945|| {{Percentage | 202945| 9083158| 1}}\n|- style=\"background:#efefef; font-weight:bold\"\n| Total population (2016) || 9,245,438|| {{Percentage | 9245438| 9245438| 1}}\n|}\n{{smalldiv|1=Source:<ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3514&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Northumberland&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3515&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Peterborough&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3543&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Simcoe&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3523&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Wellington&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3522&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Dufferin&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3518&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Durham&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3524&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Halton&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3526&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Niagara&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3520005&Geo2=CD&Code2=3520&Data=Count&SearchText=Toronto&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3530&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Waterloo&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3525005&Geo2=CD&Code2=3525&Data=Count&SearchText=Hamilton&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3528018&Geo2=CD&Code2=3528&Data=Count&SearchText=Haldimand&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3516010&Geo2=CD&Code2=3516&Data=Count&SearchText=Kawartha&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3529005&Geo2=CD&Code2=3529&Data=Count&SearchText=Brant&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3521&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Peel&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CD&Code1=3519&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=York&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1</ref>}}\n\n==Economy==\n{{Main|Economy of Toronto|Economy of Hamilton, Ontario}}\n{{update|section|date=July 2012}}\nThe economy of this region is very diverse. The [[Toronto Stock Exchange]] is the third largest in North America by market capitalization (after the [[New York Stock Exchange]] and [[Nasdaq]]), and seventh largest in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2ontario.com/welcome/bcfs_400.asp |title=Toronto Stock Exchange is the Third Largest in North America |website=2Ontario.com  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211113516/http://www.2ontario.com/welcome/bcfs_400.asp |archive-date=February 11, 2007}}</ref> \n[[File:Oakville Assembly.jpg|thumb|left|A worker installing car batteries at Ford's [[Oakville Assembly]]. The automotive industry is a major sector of the Golden Horseshoe's economy.]]\nCities including Hamilton, Oshawa, Oakville, Whitby and Kitchener all contain major large-scale industrial production facilities, Hamilton being dominated by the [[Steel#Steel industry|steel industry]] and Oakville and Oshawa primarily in the [[automotive industry]]. Other significant automotive-production facilities also exist in [[Brampton]], and [[St. Catharines]]. While manufacturing remains important to the economy of the region, the manufacturing sector has experienced a significant decline since 2000 as a result of unfavourable currency exchange rates, increasing energy costs, and reduced demand from the United States, which is by far the largest market for Ontario's goods.\n\nThe [[Hamilton-Oshawa Port Authority|Port of Hamilton]] and the [[PortsToronto|Port of Toronto]] are the two largest [[Port#Seaport|seaports]] on [[Lake Ontario]]. The [[Welland Canal]] system handles tanker ship and recreational traffic through the Great Lakes. Large rail and truck distribution facilities are located in Toronto, [[Vaughan]] and Brampton. Food processing is also a key ingredient in the economy. \n[[File:Wine grapes nearing harvest in Ontario-also example of trellis wire.jpg|thumb|The [[Niagara Peninsula]] is Canada's largest wine growing region and a major producer of [[Ontario wine]].]]\nNiagara Falls has one of the world's largest per-capita tourist economies, benefiting from millions of tourists coming to see its majestic waterfalls, shop in its numerous stores, and visit its many attractions. The winemaking and fruit growing industries of the [[Niagara Peninsula]] produce award-winning wines, which are beginning to attract attention around the world, in particular the [[ice wine]] for which the region is known.\n\nAs of 2014, sectors such as [[information technology]], health care, tourism, research and finance provide the bulk of growth in the Golden Horseshoe. The suburban cities within [[Greater Toronto]], such as [[Brampton]], [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], and [[Mississauga]], are emerging as hubs for technology and innovation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brampton.ca/EN/Business/economic-development/Key-Sectors/Pages/Innovation-and-Technology.aspx|title=Innovation & Technology|website=www.brampton.ca}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nThe Golden Horseshoe is home to several [[university|universities]], including the [[University of Toronto]] and [[McMaster University]] in Hamilton, which are ranked 1st and 4th in Canada, respectively, by the [[Academic Ranking of World Universities]]. Other universities in the region include [[Brock University]] in St. Catherines, [[Trent University]] in Peterborough, [[York University]], [[OCAD University]], [[University of Ontario Institute of Technology]] in Oshawa, [[Ryerson University]], and [[Universit\u00e9 de l'Ontario fran\u00e7ais]].\n\nPublic primary and secondary schooling is typically provided by [[school boards]], largely organized at the municipal or county/regional level. The only school board that operates throughout the Golden Horseshoe is [[Conseil scolaire Viamonde]], a public French-language school board, and [[Conseil scolaire catholique MonAvenir]], a public French-language [[separate school|separate]] school board. Both of these public French-language school boards operate across the Ontario Peninsula.\n\n==Attractions==\n{{See also|Attractions in Toronto}}\n[[File:Caribana 2009 (2).jpg|thumb|[[Toronto Caribbean Carnival]] is an annual cultural festival held in the City of Toronto.]]\nFormerly the [[List of tallest freestanding structures|tallest freestanding structure on land in the world]], the [[CN Tower]] in Toronto is among the most internationally notable attractions in the Golden Horseshoe.\n\nThe city is home to several [[shopping mall]]s such as [[Yorkdale Shopping Centre]], [[Toronto Eaton Centre]] (which is North America's busiest shopping mall),<ref>{{cite web|title=Canadian Shopping Centre Study|url=http://www.retailcouncil.org/sites/default/files/RCCCanadianShoppingCenterStudyFINAL.pdf|publisher=[[Retail Council of Canada]]|accessdate=18 January 2017|date=December 2016}}</ref> [[Scarborough Town Centre]], and [[Sherway Gardens]]. Located in the suburbs of Toronto are [[Vaughan Mills]] in [[Vaughan]], [[Bramalea City Centre]] in [[Brampton]] and [[Square One Shopping Centre]] in [[Mississauga]], the largest shopping mall in Ontario. [[Pacific Mall]], in [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], is the largest ethnic shopping mall in eastern Canada.\n\nAnnual cultural festivals that draw tourists and local alike include the Peeks Caribbean Carnival (formerly known as [[Caribana]]) and [[Taste of the Danforth]] in Toronto.\n[[File:Webster Falls - Laslovarga1.jpg|thumb|left|View of [[Webster's Falls]] in Hamilton. The falls is a part of the [[Niagara Escarpment Biosphere Reserve]], which runs across the western portion of the Golden Horseshoe.]]\nThe [[Niagara Escarpment]], a world biosphere as designated by the United Nations, runs from the north at Bruce Peninsula and then east through the region cutting the Niagara Gorge at Niagara Falls. The [[Bruce Trail]] runs along the escarpment through mostly protected woodlands. The [[Cheltenham Badlands]] in Caledon is an [[Environmental degradation|environmentally degraded]] area along the Niagara Escarpment. Similar protection of some wooded areas exists on the [[Oak Ridges Moraine]] running east\u2013west in the north end of the Greater Toronto Area, although development pressures continue to threaten the natural habitat.\n\nThe Niagara Region has become one of the major [[wine]]-production areas in Canada. The Golden Horseshoe contains many small towns with tourist-jammed, historic main streets, most notably the community of [[Niagara-on-the-Lake]], located at the mouth of the [[Niagara River]]. [[Niagara Falls, Ontario|Niagara Falls]] is one of the world's largest waterfalls, and attracts millions to [[Clifton Hill, Niagara Falls|Clifton Hill]], a neighbourhood featuring hundreds of amusements, souvenir stores, restaurants and skyline-changing hotels. Casinos here are also a huge draw.\n\n[[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] has the historical reputation of being a blue-collar city; however, waterfront redevelopments and large-scale [[gentrification]] have been rapidly changing the perception of the city, although it retains a dominant industrial base. Hamilton has over [[List of waterfalls in Hamilton, Ontario|100 waterfalls]] and cascades throughout the region.\n[[File:Leviathan Lift and Sculpture.jpg|thumb|View of [[Leviathan (roller coaster)|the Leviathan roller coaster]] at [[Canada's Wonderland]]. Located in [[Vaughan]], Wonderland is Canada's largest and most attended amusement park.]]\nThere are a number of [[Amusement park|theme parks]] in the Golden Horseshoe, all of which are seasonal. [[Canada's Wonderland]], run by [[Cedar Fair]] in Vaughan, {{convert|2|km|mi|abbr=on}} north of Vaughan Mills, is the largest and most attended theme park in Canada, as well as the most attended seasonal theme park in North America. Other theme parks include [[Wet'n'Wild Toronto]] (formerly Wild Water Kingdom) in [[Brampton]], [[African Lion Safari]] in [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] and [[Cambridge, Ontario|Cambridge]], and [[Marineland of Canada|Marineland]] in Niagara Falls.  Though not a theme park per se, the [[Exhibition Place]] hosts the annual [[Canadian National Exhibition]], which is Canada's largest annual fair.\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Toronto vs Tampa Aug 11 2018.jpg|thumb|right|A [[Toronto Blue Jays]] game at the [[Rogers Centre]] in 2018]]\nThe Golden Horseshoe is home to many professional sports teams, most of which are Toronto-based. These teams include:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Team\n!City\n!League\n!Sport\n|-\n|[[Toronto Blue Jays]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[Major League Baseball|MLB]]\n|Baseball\n|-\n|[[Toronto Raptors]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n|Basketball\n|-\n|[[Raptors 905]]\n|[[Mississauga]]\n|[[NBA G League|G League]]\n|Basketball\n|-\n|[[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]]\n|[[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]]\n|[[Canadian Football League|CFL]]\n|Canadian Football\n|-\n|[[Toronto Argonauts]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[Canadian Football League|CFL]]\n|Canadian Football\n|-\n|[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n|Ice Hockey\n|-\n|[[Toronto Marlies]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n|Ice Hockey\n|-\n|[[Toronto Rock]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[National Lacrosse League|NLL]]\n|Indoor Lacrosse\n|-\n|[[Toronto Wolfpack]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[RFL Championship|Championship]]\n|Rugby League\n|-\n|[[Toronto FC]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[Major League Soccer|MLS]]\n|Soccer\n|-\n|[[Toronto FC II]]\n|[[Toronto]]\n|[[USL League One]]\n|Soccer\n|-\n|[[Forge FC]]\n|[[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]]\n|[[Canadian Premier League|CPL]]\n|Soccer\n|-\n|[[York 9 FC|York9 FC]]\n|[[Vaughan]]\n|[[Canadian Premier League|CPL]]\n|Soccer\n|}\nThe Golden Horseshoe hosted the [[2015 Pan American Games]] and the [[2015 Parapan American Games]].\n\nUniversities' athletic teams in the Golden Horseshoe belong to [[U Sports]].\n\n==Transportation==\n{{see also|Transportation in Toronto}}\n[[File:QEW into Mississauga.png|thumb|The [[Queen Elizabeth Way]] is a major [[controlled-access highway]] that connects Greater Toronto with the Niagara Peninsula.]]\nThe Golden Horseshoe is served by an [[400-series highways|extensive network of expressways]], the backbone of which are the [[Queen Elizabeth Way]] and [[Ontario Highway 401|Highway 401]], one of the widest and busiest expressways in the world. Public transit in the region is coordinated by [[Metrolinx]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metrolinx.com/en/aboutus/about_us_index.aspx|title=About Us|agency=Metrolinx|accessdate=June 30, 2018}}</ref> Regional transit is provided by [[GO Transit]] trains and buses, and by private bus operators Greyhound and Coach Canada. Local transit is provided by municipal agencies, the largest of which is the [[Toronto Transit Commission]], which operates [[Toronto subway|three subway lines and one light metro line]] and an extensive [[Toronto Transit Commission bus system|bus]] and [[Toronto streetcar system|streetcar network]]. Toronto is currently the only city in the area with a rail-based local transit network, though its subway system extends to Vaughan as well at [[Vaughan Metropolitan Centre station]] since December 2017. However, several cities in the region have light rail lines in the works.<ref name=\"Kitchener LRT\">{{cite news|last=Outhit|first=Jeff|title=Rail yard purchased for rapid transit|url=http://www.therecord.com/news/local/article/615558--rail-yard-purchased-for-rapid-transit|accessdate=2012-04-08|newspaper=Waterloo Region Record|date=Oct 27, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Hurontario\">{{cite web|url=http://hurontario-main.ca/PDFs/masterplan/Hurontario_Master_Plan_Final_HighRes.pdf|publisher=MMM Group|title=Hurontario/Main Street Corridor Master Plan|page=578|date=October 2010|format=PDF|accessdate=2012-04-08|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324044621/http://hurontario-main.ca/PDFs/masterplan/Hurontario_Master_Plan_Final_HighRes.pdf|archivedate=2012-03-24}}</ref> These include the approved [[Hurontario LRT]] in [[Regional Municipality of Peel|Peel Region]] and [[B-Line (Hamilton)|B-Line]] in [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]].\n\nThe primary airport of the region is [[Toronto Pearson International Airport]] (officially Lester B. Pearson International Airport), located in Mississauga, which is the busiest in Canada and the [[List of busiest airports by passenger traffic|31st busiest in the world]], handling over 49.5 million passengers in 2018, and offering non-stop flights worldwide where it ranks [[List of busiest airports by aircraft movements|13th in the world]]. Other regional airports of significance include [[John C. Munro Hamilton International Airport]] located in southern Hamilton, which is a major regional freight and courier location as well as the [[Region of Waterloo International Airport]] in Kitchener; [[Buttonville Municipal Airport|Buttonville Airport]] and [[Billy Bishop Toronto City Airport|Billy Bishop airport]] in the [[Greater Toronto Area]], both of which mostly serve regional business travellers but the latter being the third largest in the region for passenger volume. Within driving distance is [[Buffalo Niagara International Airport]] in [[Cheektowaga, New York]], in the United States. Buffalo Niagara carries the second largest passenger volume in the region, serving over 5 million passengers in 2018.<ref>https://www.wgrz.com/article/travel/bnia-celebrates-major-milestone/71-63d09d28-eb5f-454a-952b-ff4ff4ff7a61</ref> It is frequently used by Canadian passengers flying to US destinations.\n\n==Divisions==\n{{see also|Greater Toronto and Hamilton Area}}\n[[File:Downtown Toronto in September 2018 (Early Sunday Morning, view from a kayak).jpg|right|thumb|alt=A spear-like tower is between a white-domed structure and small buildings on the left, and increasingly taller buildings to the right. In the foreground is a lake, with a few visible buoys, and the background is a deep blue sky with a few clouds near the horizon.|Skyline of [[Downtown Toronto]]. The city is the financial anchor of the Golden Horseshoe.]]\n[[Image:HamiltonOntarioSkylineC.JPG|right|thumb|alt=A tree-lined highway is in the foreground, angled diagonally from bottom right to middle left of the image. Buildings are in the centre, and the background is a sky meeting rolling hills in the distance.|[[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] lies at the western edge of [[Lake Ontario]].]]\n[[File:Cataratas del Ni\u00e1gara 31.jpg|thumb|alt=A spike tower with a pod is lit along its length on the right. Other buildings sit on the right while a river and large waterfall occupies the left.|[[Niagara Falls, Ontario|Niagara Falls]] is a major tourist destination, situated at the southern portion of the Golden Horseshoe.]]\n\n===Municipalities===\n{{see also|List of municipalities in the Greater Toronto Area}}\n<!-- populations come from each article, which in turn come from the 2016 Census -->\n<!-- list of municipalities comes from here: http://placestogrow.ca/index.php?Itemid=14&id=430&option=com_content&task=view -->\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Section\n! Census division\n! Population\n|-\n| Core || [[Regional Municipality of Durham|Durham Region]] || 645,862\n|-\n| Core || [[Regional Municipality of Halton|Halton Region]] || 548,435\n|-\n| Core || [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] || 536,917\n|-\n| Core || [[Regional Municipality of Niagara|Niagara Region]] || 447,888\n|-\n| Core || [[Regional Municipality of Peel|Peel Region]] || 1,381,739\n|-\n| Core || [[Toronto]] || 2,731,571\n|-\n| Core || [[Regional Municipality of York|York Region]] || 1,109,909\n|-\n| Core \n|data-sort-value=\"zzzz\"| ''Total core'' || ''7,402,321''\n|-\n| Extended || Brant ([[County of Brant]] and [[Brantford]]) ||134,808\n|-\n| Extended || [[Dufferin County]] || 61,735\n|-\n| Extended || [[Haldimand County]] || \t44,876\n|-\n| Extended || [[Kawartha Lakes]] || 75,423\n|-\n| Extended || [[Northumberland County, Ontario|Northumberland County]] || 85,598\n|-\n| Extended || Peterborough ([[Peterborough County]] and the city of [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]])|| 138,236\n|-\n| Extended || Simcoe ([[Simcoe County]], [[Barrie]] and [[Orillia]]) || 479,650\n|-\n| Extended || [[Waterloo Region]] || 535,154\n|-\n| Extended || Wellington ([[Wellington County, Ontario|Wellington County]] and [[Guelph]]) || 222,726\n|-\n|-\n| Extended\n| data-sort-value=\"zzzy\"| ''Total extended'' || ''1,778,206''\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"zzzz\"| '''Total''' ||'''all''' || '''9,180,527'''\n|}\n\n===Census metropolitan areas===\nPopulation figures are from the 2016 census.\n\nThe [[census metropolitan area]]s listed below are within the Greater Golden Horseshoe. Not all land within the Greater Golden Horseshoe is part of a Census Metropolitan Area; some Census Metropolitan Areas are partly in the Golden Horseshoe and partly outside it.\n\n# [[Toronto]] 5,928,040<!--Peel and York Regions are completely within Toronto CMA-->\n# [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] 747,545\n# [[St. Catharines]]-[[Regional Municipality of Niagara|Niagara]] 406,074\n# [[Oshawa]] 379,848\n# [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]]-[[Cambridge, Ontario|Cambridge]]-[[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]] 523,894\n# [[Barrie]] 197,059\n# [[Guelph]] 151,984\n# [[Brantford]] 134,203\n# [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]] 121,721\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{wikivoyage-inline|Golden Horseshoe}}\n*[https://www.cityofwaterfalls.ca/ The City Of Waterfalls]\n*\n\n{{Subdivisions of Ontario}}\n{{Canadian City Geographic Location (8-way)\n | Northwest = [[Georgian Triangle]]\n | North = [[Central Ontario]]\n | Northeast = [[Central Ontario]] / [[Eastern Ontario]]\n | West = [[Southwestern Ontario]]\n | Centre = Golden Horseshoe\n | East = [[Eastern Ontario]] / [[Western New York]]\n | Southwest = [[Southwestern Ontario]]\n | South = [[Upstate New York]] / [[Niagara Frontier]]\n | Southeast = ''[[Lake Ontario]]'' / [[Finger Lakes]]\n | image = \n}}\n{{Portal bar|Ontario|Canada}}\n\n[[Category:Metropolitan areas of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Geographic regions of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Golden Horseshoe| ]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1950s]]\n", "name_user": "Sagacity53", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEducation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_Horseshoe"}
{"title_page": "Negative equity", "text_new": "{{Globalize|article|USA|2name=the United States|date=October 2016}}\n'''Negative equity''' occurs when the value of an asset used to secure a loan is less than the outstanding balance on the loan.<ref>[http://www.economist.com/world/unitedstates/displayStory.cfm?story_id=13145239 America's foreclosure plan: Can\u2019t pay or won\u2019t pay?], Paragraph 5, ''[[The Economist]]'' (February 19, 2009).</ref>  In the United States, assets (particularly [[real estate]], whose loans are [[Mortgage loan|mortgages]]) with negative equity are often referred to as being \"'''underwater'''\", and loans and borrowers with negative equity are said to be \"'''upside down'''\". \n\nPeople and companies alike may have negative equity, as reflected on their [[balance sheet]]s.\n\n==History==\nThe term negative equity was widely used in the [[United Kingdom]] during the economic [[Early 1990s recession|recession between 1991 and 1996]], and in [[Hong Kong]] between 1998 and 2003. These recessions led to increased unemployment and a decline in property prices, which in turn led to an increase in [[repossession]]s by banks and [[Building society|building societies]] of properties worth less than the outstanding debt.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/negative-equity-set-to-pass-into-housing-history-1358889.html |title=Negative equity set to pass into housing history |date=October 18, 1996 |publisher=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nSince 2007, those most exposed to negative equity are borrowers who obtained loans of a high percentage of the property value (such as 90% or even 100%). These were commonly available before the [[credit crunch]]. Such cases are of course the most at risk from falls in property value.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n== In an asset ==\nIn the owner-occupied [[real estate economics|housing market]], a fall in the [[market value]] of a [[Mortgage loan|mortgaged]] house or apartment/flat is the usual cause of negative equity. It may occur when the property owner obtains second-mortgage [[home equity loan]]s, causing the combined loans to exceed the home value, or simply because the original mortgage was too generous. If the borrower defaults, [[repossession]] and sale of the property by the lender will not raise enough cash to repay the amount outstanding, and the borrower will still be in [[debt]] as well as having lost the property. Some US states like [[California]] require lenders to choose between going after the borrower or taking repossession, but not both.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nIt is also common for negative equity to occur when the   value of a good drops shortly after its purchase. This occurs frequently in automobile loans, where the market value of a car might drop by 20-30% as soon as the car is driven off the lot.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nWhile typically a result of fluctuating asset prices, negative equity can occur when the value of the asset stays fixed and the loan balance increases because loan payments are less than the interest, a situation known as [[negative amortization]]. The typical assets securing such loans are [[real property]] \u2013 commercial, office or residential. When the loan is [[Nonrecourse debt|nonrecourse]], the lender can only look to the security, that is, the value of the property, when the borrower fails to repay the loan.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n== Negative net worth ==\nA person who has negative equity can be said to have \"negative net worth\", where the person's liabilities exceed their assets. One might come to have negative equity as a result of taking out a substantial, unsecured loan. For example, one might use a [[student loan]] to pursue higher education. Although education increases the likelihood of higher future earnings, potential alone is not a financial asset. {{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nIn the United States, [[student loans]] are rarely dischargeable in [[bankruptcy]], and typically lenders provide student loans without requiring security. This stands in contrast to lenders requiring borrowers to have an equity stake in a comparably-sized real estate loan, as described above, secured by both a down payment and a mortgage. An explanation for the willingness of creditors to provide unsecured student loans is that, in a practical sense, American student loans are secured by the borrower's future earnings. This is so since creditors may legally garnish wages when a borrower defaults.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.creditosenusa.com/hipotecas-underwater/|title=Qu\u00e9 son las hipotecas underwater|date=2020-03-25|website=Cr\u00e9ditos en USA|language=es|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== Effects ==\nA homeowner who is under water might be financially incapable of selling their current house and buying another one.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zillow's Humphries on U.S. Housing Market Outlook|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/video/zillow-s-humphries-on-u-s-housing-market-outlook-4Pd_Q7stQ7WpSRarylLKdQ.html|work=bloomberg.com|publisher=BLOOMBERG L.P.|accessdate=24 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Mortgage loan]]s\n* [[Negative amortization]]\n* [[Loss mitigation]]\n* [[Strategic default]]\n* [[Equity (finance)]]\n* [[Home equity protection]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading==\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Irwin\n  | first = Robert \n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = Home Seller's Checklist: Everything You Need to Know to Get the Highest Price for Your House\n  | publisher = McGraw-Hill Professional\n  | date =\n  | location =\n  | url =\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | page = 180\n}}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Nerad\n  | first = Jack \n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = The Complete Idiot's Guide to Buying or Leasing a Car\n  | publisher =\n  | year = 1996\n  | location =\n  | url =https://archive.org/details/completeidiotsgu00nera_0\n  | url-access = registration\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | page = [https://archive.org/details/completeidiotsgu00nera_0/page/129 129]\n}}\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20080412081731/http://www.edmunds.com/advice/strategies/articles/104952/article.html\n*http://money.cnn.com/2005/08/04/real_estate/buying_selling/home_equity_falling/\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Negative Equity}}\n[[Category:Mortgage]]\n[[Category:Credit]]\n[[Category:United States housing bubble]]\n[[Category:Negative concepts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Globalize|article|USA|2name=the United States|date=October 2016}}\n'''Negative equity''' occurs when the value of an asset used to secure a loan is less than the outstanding balance on the loan.<ref>[http://www.economist.com/world/unitedstates/displayStory.cfm?story_id=13145239 America's foreclosure plan: Can\u2019t pay or won\u2019t pay?], Paragraph 5, ''[[The Economist]]'' (February 19, 2009).</ref>  In the United States, assets (particularly [[real estate]], whose loans are [[Mortgage loan|mortgages]]) with negative equity are often referred to as being \"'''underwater'''\", and loans and borrowers with negative equity are said to be \"'''upside down'''\". \n\nPeople and companies alike may have negative equity, as reflected on their [[balance sheet]]s.\n\n==History==\nThe term negative equity was widely used in the [[United Kingdom]] during the economic [[Early 1990s recession|recession between 1991 and 1996]], and in [[Hong Kong]] between 1998 and 2003. These recessions led to increased unemployment and a decline in property prices, which in turn led to an increase in [[repossession]]s by banks and [[Building society|building societies]] of properties worth less than the outstanding debt.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/negative-equity-set-to-pass-into-housing-history-1358889.html |title=Negative equity set to pass into housing history |date=October 18, 1996 |publisher=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nSince 2007, those most exposed to negative equity are borrowers who obtained loans of a high percentage of the property value (such as 90% or even 100%). These were commonly available before the [[credit crunch]]. Such cases are of course the most at risk from falls in property value.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n== In an asset ==\nIn the owner-occupied [[real estate economics|housing market]], a fall in the [[market value]] of a [[Mortgage loan|mortgaged]] house or apartment/flat is the usual cause of negative equity. It may occur when the property owner obtains second-mortgage [[home equity loan]]s, causing the combined loans to exceed the home value, or simply because the original mortgage was too generous. If the borrower defaults, [[repossession]] and sale of the property by the lender will not raise enough cash to repay the amount outstanding, and the borrower will still be in [[debt]] as well as having lost the property. Some US states like [[California]] require lenders to choose between going after the borrower or taking repossession, but not both.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nIt is also common for negative equity to occur when the   value of a good drops shortly after its purchase. This occurs frequently in automobile loans, where the market value of a car might drop by 20-30% as soon as the car is driven off the lot.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nWhile typically a result of fluctuating asset prices, negative equity can occur when the value of the asset stays fixed and the loan balance increases because loan payments are less than the interest, a situation known as [[negative amortization]]. The typical assets securing such loans are [[real property]] \u2013 commercial, office or residential. When the loan is [[Nonrecourse debt|nonrecourse]], the lender can only look to the security, that is, the value of the property, when the borrower fails to repay the loan.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n== Negative net worth ==\nA person who has negative equity can be said to have \"negative net worth\", where the person's liabilities exceed their assets. One might come to have negative equity as a result of taking out a substantial, unsecured loan. For example, one might use a [[student loan]] to pursue higher education. Although education increases the likelihood of higher future earnings, potential alone is not a financial asset. {{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nIn the United States, [[student loans]] are rarely dischargeable in [[bankruptcy]], and typically lenders provide student loans without requiring security. This stands in contrast to lenders requiring borrowers to have an equity stake in a comparably-sized real estate loan, as described above, secured by both a down payment and a mortgage. An explanation for the willingness of creditors to provide unsecured student loans is that, in a practical sense, American student loans are secured by the borrower's future earnings. This is so since creditors may legally garnish wages when a borrower defaults.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n== Effects ==\nA homeowner who is under water might be financially incapable of selling their current house and buying another one.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zillow's Humphries on U.S. Housing Market Outlook|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/video/zillow-s-humphries-on-u-s-housing-market-outlook-4Pd_Q7stQ7WpSRarylLKdQ.html|work=bloomberg.com|publisher=BLOOMBERG L.P.|accessdate=24 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Mortgage loan]]s\n* [[Negative amortization]]\n* [[Loss mitigation]]\n* [[Strategic default]]\n* [[Equity (finance)]]\n* [[Home equity protection]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading==\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Irwin\n  | first = Robert \n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = Home Seller's Checklist: Everything You Need to Know to Get the Highest Price for Your House\n  | publisher = McGraw-Hill Professional\n  | date =\n  | location =\n  | url =\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | page = 180\n}}\n*{{cite book\n  | la