{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-3}}\n'''Promotional tours'''\n* [[Flicker Sessions 2017|Flicker Sessions]] (2017)\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Billboard Social 50 number-one artists]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Niall Horan}}\n*[http://www.niallhoran.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Niall Horan}}\n{{One Direction}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Horan, Niall}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish singers]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:Folk-pop singers]]\n[[Category:Irish guitarists]]\n[[Category:Irish male singers]]\n[[Category:Irish pop singers]]\n[[Category:Irish singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:One Direction members]]\n[[Category:People from Mullingar]]\n[[Category:Pop rock singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish singer-songwriter}}\n{{about|the singer|the priest|Neil Horan|the rugby union player|Niall Hogan}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Niall Horan\n| image              = Niall Horan Portrait.jpg\n| caption            = Horan in 2016\n| birth_name         = Niall James Horan\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1993|9|13}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mullingar]], [[County Westmeath|Westmeath]], Ireland\n| net_worth          = $71 million (approx)\n| years_active       = 2010\u2013present\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer-songwriter}}\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Niall Horan|Full list]]\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist |embed=yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| instruments     = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar|piano}}\n| genre           = {{hlist|[[Pop rock]]|[[folk-pop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/niall-horan-dials-up-his-pop-rock-sound-on-new-single-nice-to-meet-ya__27431/|title=Niall Horan dials up his pop-rock sound on new single Nice To Meet Ya|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|first=Rob|last=Copsey|date=3 October 2019|accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>}}\n| label           = {{hlist|[[Syco Music|Syco]]|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]|[[Capitol Records|Capitol]]}}\n| associated_acts = [[One Direction]]\n| website         = {{URL|Niallhoran.com}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Niall James Horan''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|n|a\u026a|\u0259|l|_|\u02c8|h|\u0252r|\u0259n}};<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YHD0Z71JU6M|title=Niall Horan's totally fake interview|work=BBC Radio 1|via=YouTube|accessdate=24 May 2018}}</ref> born 13 September 1993) is an Irish singer-songwriter. He rose to prominence as a member of the band [[One Direction]]. In 2010, Horan auditioned as a solo contestant for British singing competition ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]''. After being eliminated as solo performers, Niall, [[Liam Payne]], [[Louis Tomlinson]], [[Zayn Malik]], and [[Harry Styles]] were put together in a band.\n\nFollowing the band's hiatus in 2016, Horan signed a recording deal as a solo artist with [[Capitol Records]]. His singles \"[[This Town (Niall Horan song)|This Town]]\" and \"[[Slow Hands (Niall Horan song)|Slow Hands]]\" from his debut studio album ''[[Flicker (album)|Flicker]]'' (2017) reached the top 20 in several countries. The album debuted at number one in Ireland and the United States, as well as charting within the top three in Australia and the UK. He embarked on the [[Flicker Sessions]] tour (2017) and the [[Flicker World Tour]] (2018) to support the album. Horan's second studio album, ''[[Heartbreak Weather]]'', was released on March 13, 2020 and debuted at number four on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/9340275/lil-uzi-vert-eternal-atake-billboard-200-no-1|title=Lil Uzi Vert's 'Eternal Atake' Spends Second Week at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=22 March 2020|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nNiall James Horan was born on 13 September 1993 in [[Mullingar]], [[County Westmeath|Westmeath]], Ireland. He has an older brother, Greg Horan.<ref>{{cite news|author=Lisa McGarry|url=http://www.unrealitytv.co.uk/x-factor/x-factor-2010-niall-horans-brother-says-one-direction-get-along-well|title=X Factor 2010: Niall Horan's brother says One Direction get along well|website=Unrealitytv.co.uk|date=6 November 2010|accessdate=17 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318230602/http://www.unrealitytv.co.uk/x-factor/x-factor-2010-niall-horans-brother-says-one-direction-get-along-well/|archivedate=18 March 2012}}</ref> His parents, Bobby Horan and Maura Gallagher, divorced when he was five years old, so he and his brother, Greg, lived with their mother for a year. After spending a year apart from their father, they later decided to move in with him.<ref name=\"daily record\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-interviews/2012/04/16/mums-of-one-direction-stars-reveal-how-the-boys-have-grown-into-music-sensations-86908-23826535|title=Mums of One Direction stars reveal how the boys have grown into music sensations|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]| location= Glasgow|date=16 April 2012|accessdate=11 May 2012}}</ref> He had asthma as a child. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pflmIVb5Mbg |title=Niall Horan Answers the Web's Most Searched Questions &#124; WIRED |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2019-10-18 |accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> He attended St. Kenny's National School, a primary school, and [[Col\u00e1iste Mhuire, Mullingar|Col\u00e1iste Mhuire]], a Catholic boys school, which are both located in Mullingar.\n\nHoran tried to play the guitar that his brother got for Christmas, but was not able to play it. Horan, then aged 11, taught himself how to play the guitar by following YouTube tutorials. His aunt discovered his talent one day when she was in the car with Horan as he started singing. She originally thought the radio was on. As a teenager, he performed at the Mullingar Arts Centre during a fund-raiser for the local football team, the Shamrocks. He was also bagging a support slot with former ''X Factor'' contestant [[Lloyd Daniels (singer)|Lloyd Daniels]] at the Academy club in Dublin.<ref>{{cite web|last1=John D. Buchanan|title=Niall Horan Bio|url=https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/store/music/artist/niall-horan/0ddd3f00-0200-11db-89ca-0019b92a3933/bio?display=grid|website=microsoft|accessdate=26 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===2010: ''The X Factor''===\nIn 2010, at sixteen years old, Horan auditioned for the [[The X Factor (UK series 7)|seventh series]] of ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]'' in Dublin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Niall Auditions For The X Factor|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/one-direction/photos/niall-horan-best-pictures/#x-factor-audition|website=Capital FM|accessdate=31 December 2015}}</ref> He sang \"[[So Sick]]\" and received mixed comments from the judges. [[Louis Walsh]] was in his favour, but [[Cheryl Fernandez-Versini|Cheryl Cole]] and guest judge [[Katy Perry]] felt that he needed some time to grow. [[Simon Cowell]] voted to let him through, Cole said no, Walsh said yes, and Perry decided to vote yes.  Horan was then put through to bootcamp.\n\n[[File:One Direction X Factor Live Glasgow 2.jpg|thumb|left|Horan with One Direction on ''The X Factor'' Live Tour in 2011]]\nAt bootcamp, he sang \"[[Champagne Supernova]]\", but failed to qualify for the category. After a suggestion from guest judge [[Nicole Scherzinger]], Horan was put in a group with four boys who also failed to move on in the competition, and since they were too good to let go, the judges decided to agree with Scherzinger. Horan along with Harry Styles, Liam Payne, Louis Tomlinson, and Zayn Malik formed One Direction. Styles came up with the band name, which he thought would sound good when announcer [[Peter Dickson (announcer)|Peter Dickson]] read their name out on the live shows.\n\nThe group got together for two weeks to get to know each other and to practice. For their qualifying song at the \"judges' houses\" and their first song as a group, One Direction sang an acoustic version of \"[[Torn (Ednaswap song)|Torn]]\". Simon Cowell later commented that the performance convinced him that the group \"were confident, fun, like a gang of friends, and kind of fearless as well.\" Within the first four weeks of the live shows, they were Cowell's last act in the competition. During the competition, the band performed different songs such as [[Kelly Clarkson]]'s \"[[My Life Would Suck Without You]]\" and [[Bonnie Tyler]]'s \"[[Total Eclipse of the Heart]]\", quickly gaining popularity in the Silver Islands. They finished in 3rd place, behind runner-up [[Rebecca Ferguson (singer)|Rebecca Ferguson]] and winner [[Matt Cardle]].\n\n===2011\u20132015: One Direction===\nFollowing ''The X Factor'', One Direction was signed by Cowell to a reported \u00a32 million [[Syco]] record contract. They began recording their debut album in Los Angeles in January 2011. That February, a book licensed by One Direction, ''One Direction: Forever Young (Our Official X Factor Story)'', was released and topped ''[[The Sunday Times]]''' Best Seller list. That same month, the band and other contestants from the series participated in ''The X Factor Live Tour''. During the tour, the group performed for 500,000 people throughout the UK. After the tour concluded in April, the group continued working on their debut album. Recording took place in Stockholm, London, and Los Angeles, as One Direction worked with producers such as [[Carl Falk]], [[Savan Kotecha]], [[Steve Mac]], and [[Rami Yacoub]].\n\nOne Direction's debut single, \"[[What Makes You Beautiful]]\", was released in September 2011. A global and commercial success, the song reached number one in several countries.<ref>{{cite web|title=One Direction on UK|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/one%20direction/|website=The Official Chart Company|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mexico Airplay |url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/internationalcharts/mexico |accessdate=1 January 2016 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69HQ7r3yp?url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/internationalcharts/mexico |archivedate=19 July 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Chart Track Archive|url=http://www.chart-track.co.uk/index.jsp?c=p%2Fmusicvideo%2Fmusic%2Farchive%2Findex_test.jsp&ct=240001&arch=t&lyr=2011&year=2011&week=37|website=GFK Chart Track|accessdate=1 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827045450/http://www.chart-track.co.uk/index.jsp?c=p%2Fmusicvideo%2Fmusic%2Farchive%2Findex_test.jsp&ct=240001&arch=t&lyr=2011&year=2011&week=37|archive-date=27 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7408939/ask-billboard-one-directions-career-sales |title = Ask Billboard: One Direction's Career Sales}}</ref> Subsequent singles, \"[[Gotta Be You (One Direction song)|Gotta Be You]]\", \"[[One Thing (One Direction song)|One Thing]]\", and \"[[More than This (One Direction song)|More than This]]\", had moderate success,<ref>{{cite web|title=More Than This on Charts|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=One+Direction&titel=More+Than+This&cat=s|website=Hung Medien|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=One Thing on Charts|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=One+Direction&titel=One+Thing&cat=s|website=Hung Medien|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gotta Be You on Charts|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=One+Direction&titel=Gotta+Be+You&cat=s|website=Hung Medien|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref> with the first two becoming top ten hits in the UK. In November of that year, the group's debut album \"[[Up All Night (One Direction album)|Up All Night]]\" was released in Ireland and the UK, reaching number one and number two on the charts, respectively. The album was released internationally in March 2012, and One Direction became the first [[United Kingdom|UK]] group to have their debut album reach number one in the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.idolator.com/6226811/one-direction-debut-chart-history?safari=1&Exc_D_LessThanPoint002_p1=1 | title=One Direction Debut at #1, Make Album Chart History| date=2012-03-21}}</ref> To promote the album, they embarked on their first headlining concert tour, the [[Up All Night Tour]]. Originally intended with shows taking place only in the UK and Ireland, additional dates in North America and Australia were added due to extreme demand. The tour was a commercial success; tickets sold out in minutes, and the tour was met with positive reviews from critics who applauded their singing abilities and stage presence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=HSWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.heraldsun.com.au%2Fentertainment%2Fone-direction-infection-sweeps-melbourne%2Fnews-story%2Fd24bd97352b8eb096d0a8ddf59405a03&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=1a453d45df66c2a29080c90b37921a4a-1570174837|title=Heraldsun.com.au {{!}} Subscribe to the Herald Sun for exclusive stories|website=Heraldsun.com.au|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> In May 2012, the band released the tour's DVD, [[Up All Night: The Live Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Up All Night \u2013 Live Concert DVD|url=http://www.onedirectionmusic.com/gb/releases/entry/up_all_night_-_live_concert_dvd/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319035131/http://www.onedirectionmusic.com/gb/releases/entry/up_all_night_-_live_concert_dvd|archive-date=19 March 2012|url-status=dead|website=One Direction Music|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=One Direction prepare for 'Up All Night' Tour With Watford Concert|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/one-direction/news/up-all-night-tour-watford/|archive-url=http://www.freezepage.com/1333935031UMDTEVHWRV?url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/one-direction/news/up-all-night-tour-watford/|url-status=dead|archive-date=9 April 2012|website=Capital FM|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref> That same month, One Direction's first book to be licensed in America, ''Dare to Dream: Life as One Direction'', was published and topped [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]].<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2012-06-10/paperback-books/list.html |work=The New York Times | title=Best Sellers | date=10 June 2012 | accessdate = 24 August 2012 | first=Gregory | last=Cowles}}</ref> In September 2012, the group released \"[[Live While We're Young]]\", the lead single from their upcoming second album. The album's second single, \"[[Little Things (One Direction song)|Little Things]],\" spawned the band's second [[List of UK Singles Chart number ones of the 2010s|number one single]] in the UK.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/one-direction-score-number-1-single-and-album-__2564/ | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830142315/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/one-direction-score-number-1-single-and-album-__2564/ | archivedate=2018-08-30 |title = One Direction score Number 1 single AND album!}}</ref> In November 2012, ''[[Take Me Home (One Direction album)|Take Me Home]]'', One Direction's sophomore album, was released. It reached number one in over 35 countries,<ref>{{cite web|title=Irish Albums Chart \u2013 Take Me Home|url=http://www.chart-track.co.uk/index.jsp?c=p/musicvideo/music/archive/index_test.jsp&ct=240002&arch=t&lyr=2012&year=2012&week=46|website=GFK Chart Track|accessdate=1 January 2016|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Cqwb9Iql?url=http://www.chart-track.co.uk/index.jsp?c=p/musicvideo/music/archive/index_test.jsp&ct=240002&arch=t&lyr=2012&year=2012&week=46|archive-date=12 December 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=One Direction Chart History (Billboard 200)|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/artist/one-direction/chart-history/1748710?f=305&g=Albums|website=Billboard|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=One Direction Chart History (Canadian Albums)|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/artist/one-direction/chart-history/1748710?f=309&g=Albums|website=Billboard|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Australian Album Charts \u2013 One Direction|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=One+Direction&titel=Take+Me+Home&cat=a|website=Hung Medien|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref> and, after reaching number one on the ''[[Billboard 200]]'', the group became the first boy band in US chart history to record two number-one albums in the same calendar year alongside becoming the first group since 2008 to record two number-one albums in the same year.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474059/one-directions-take-me-home-debuts-at-no-1-with-years-third-biggest-opening |title = One Direction's 'Take Me Home' Debuts at No. 1 with Year's Third-Biggest Opening}}</ref> To support the album, they embarked on their second headlining tour, the [[Take Me Home Tour (One Direction)|Take Me Home Tour]], playing over 120 shows over four continents. In August 2013, ''[[One Direction: This Is Us]]'', a [[3D film|3-D]] [[documentary]] [[concert film]] was released and was a box office success, grossing over $68.5 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/aug/20/one-direction-fans-film-premiere|title=One Direction fans queue for prime view of a global success story|last=Sullivan|first=Caroline|date=2013-08-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-10-04|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=onedirection.htm|title=One Direction: This is Us|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=One Direction Movie in 3D|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/films.php?id=90812|website=Coming Soon|accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref> One Direction's third book, ''One Direction: Where We Are: Our Band, Our Story: 100% Official'', was released that same month.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/one-direction-announces-we-are-556785 |title = One Direction Announces 'Where We Are' Book}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Niall Horan (20837719742).jpg|thumb|right|252px|Horan during the [[On the Road Again Tour]] at [[Soldier Field]], [[Chicago]] in 2015]]\n\nThe band's third studio album, ''[[Midnight Memories]]'', was released on 25 November 2013. It was the best-selling album worldwide in 2013 with 4 million copies sold globally.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-28599903 | title=One Direction top global album chart| work=BBC News| date=August 2014}}</ref> \"[[Best Song Ever]]\", the album's lead single, is One Direction's highest charting single in the US to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/one-direction|title=One Direction Chart History|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> Following the album's released, the group embarked on the [[Where We Are Tour (One Direction)|Where We Are Tour]]. The band's first all-stadium tour, tickets sold out in minutes,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/one-direction/news/one-direction-tour-tickets-sell-out-in-minutes |title = One Direction Tour Tickets Sell Out in Minutes |work=MTV UK}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://metro.co.uk/2013/05/25/fans-left-devastated-as-one-direction-where-we-are-tour-tickets-sell-out-in-minutes-3808314/ | title=1D add tour dates after 'instant sell-out'| date=2013-05-25}}</ref> and more shows were added due to \"overwhelming demand.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/news/2013/12/4/18541298/one-direction-adds-show-to-chicago-stop-on-tour |title = One Direction adds show to Chicago stop on tour|date = 2013-12-04}}</ref> The band averaged 49,848 fans per show.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6281518/one-direction-where-we-are-tour-three-million|title=One Direction's Where We Are Tour Attended by 3.4 Million Fans|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> The tour grossed over $290 million and was the highest-grossing tour of 2014, the 15th [[List of highest-grossing concert tours|highest-grossing concert tour]] of all time, and is still the highest-grossing tour of all time by a vocal group.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2015/03/24/these-were-the-10-highest-grossing-tours-of-2014/#673c117c3643 |title = These Were the 10 Highest-Grossing Tours of 2014|website=Forbes.com}}</ref> In September 2014, One Direction's fourth book, ''One Direction: Who We Are: Our Official Autobiography'' was released. The group's second [[concert film]], ''[[One Direction: Where We Are \u2013 The Concert Film]]'', was released in October 2014, showing footage of the band's shows at [[San Siro Stadium]] in [[Milan, Italy]]. In November 2014, One Direction released their fourth album, ''[[Four (One Direction album)|Four]]''. The last album to include [[Zayn Malik]], singles \"[[Steal My Girl]]\" and \"[[Night Changes]]\" both received platinum status.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=One+Direction&ti=Steal+My+Girl#search_section |title = Gold & Platinum|website=Riaa.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=One+Direction&ti=Night+Changes#search_section |title = Gold & Platinum|website=Riaa.com}}</ref> The album debuted number one in 18 countries,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.lthqofficial.com/news/2018/11/17/fourth-anniversary-of-one-directions-album-four |title = Fourth Anniversary of One Direction's Album, Four|website=Lthqofficial.com}}</ref> and One Direction became the only group in the 58-year history of the [[Billboard Hot 200|''Billboard'' 200]] albums chart to have their first four albums debut at number one.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Caufield|first1=Keith|title=One Direction's 'Four' Makes Historic No. 1 Debut on Billboard 200 Chart|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6327789/one-direction-four-no-1-debut-billboard-200|website=Billboard.com|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> In February 2015, the band embarked on the [[On The Road Again Tour]], playing shows in Australia, Asia, Africa, Europe, and North America. Over 2.3 million tickets were sold with a gross of $208 million. In November 2015, ''[[Made in the A.M.]]'', their fifth album, was released. Led by singles \"[[Drag Me Down]]\" and \"[[Perfect (One Direction song)|Perfect]]\", the album reached number one in multiple countries, including the UK, while it reached number two on the US ''[[Billboard 200]]''. Following the release of the album the group went on an indefinite hiatus.<ref>{{cite web|title=One Direction to 'take a break in 2016' after release of fifth album|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/34037397/one-direction-to-take-a-break-in-2016-after-release-of-fifth-album|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=16 October 2017|date=24 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lipshutz|first1=Jason|title=One Direction & Justin Bieber Album Release Showdown Set for November 13?|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6706833/one-direction-justin-bieber-album-release-november-13-poll|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=16 October 2017|date=9 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u20132018: ''Flicker'' and Modest Golf Management===\nIn February 2016, Modest Golf, a golf management company that Horan founded together with Mark McDonnell and Ian Watts, was released. Modest Golf has since signed several golf players. In March 2019, Modest Golf earned its first European tour win when Italian golfer [[Guido Migliozzi]], the first golfer that the company signed back in August 2016, won the Kenyan Open.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bunkered.co.uk/golf-news/niall-horan-we-are-in-this-to-grow-the-game|title=Niall Horan - \"We are in this to grow the game\"|website=Bunkered.com|accessdate=19 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://golfweek.com/2019/03/17/golf-euro-tour-niall-horan/|title=Niall Horan's management company gets first European Tour win|website=Golfweek.com|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, it was announced that Horan had signed a solo deal with [[Capitol Records]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Rumor Mill|title=Niall In the Family|url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/news&id=302822|website=HITS Daily Double|publisher=HITS Digital Ventures|accessdate=8 September 2016|location=United States|date=7 September 2016}}</ref> On 29 September 2016, Horan released his debut solo single \"[[This Town (Niall Horan song)|This Town]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/niall-horan-surprises-fans-dropping-8941954|title=Niall Horan surprises fans by dropping his FIRST solo single This Town|first=Katy|last=Forrester|date=29 September 2016|website=Mirror.co.uk|accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref> Since its release, it has peaked at number 9 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/search/artists/niall%20horan/|title=Niall Horan > UK Charts|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=8 October 2016}}</ref> and number 20 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"Hot 100\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7640667/hot-100-rae-sremmurd-migos-bad-boujee|title=Rae Sremmurd Returns to No. 1 on Hot 100, Migos Soars to Top 10|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=3 January 2017|accessdate=4 January 2017}}</ref> On 4 May 2017, Horan released his second solo single \"[[Slow Hands (Niall Horan song)|Slow Hands]]\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7777051/niall-horan-single-slow-hands-release-date |title=Niall Horan's Next Single 'Slow Hands' Has a Release Date |date=1 May 2017 |work=Billboard |access-date=2 May 2017}}</ref> It also entered the top 10 in the UK and the top 20 in the US.\n\nIn an interview with ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', Horan stated that his upcoming album, ''[[Flicker (album)|Flicker]]'', was inspired by classic rock acts, including [[Fleetwood Mac]] and [[Eagles (band)|The Eagles]], \"Whenever I would pick up a guitar, I would always naturally play chords like that, and finger pick a lot and play that folky kind of style.\" He also described the collection as having a \"folk-with-pop feel to it.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://ew.com/music/2017/05/04/niall-horan-slow-hands-new-song/ |title=Niall Horan gets funky on new track, 'Slow Hands' |date=4 May 2017 |work=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=29 May 2017}}</ref> Horan embarked on a worldwide tour, [[Flicker Sessions 2017]], which started in August to promote the album.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/niall-horan-plots-intimate-flicker-sessions-2017-world-tour-w491538 |title=Niall Horan Plots Intimate 'Flicker Sessions 2017' World Tour |last=Reed |first=Ryan |date=10 July 2017 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=10 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nHoran announced that he had contacted American singer [[Maren Morris]] to contribute to his song \"[[Seeing Blind]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/niall-horan-maren-morris-duet-sam-smith-new-album-capitol-congress-1202522055/|title=Niall Horan Debuts Duet With Maren Morris, Sam Smith Reveals New Album Details at Capitol Congress|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Halperin|first=Shirley|date=9 August 2017|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref> In August, he debuted a song titled \"On My Own\" at Dublin's [[Olympia Theatre (Dublin)|Olympia Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2017/0829/900898-niall-horan/|title=Niall Horan unveils debut album at Olympia show|work=[[RT\u00c9.ie]]|date=29 August 2017|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref> On 15 September 2017, Horan released his third single from the album, \"[[Too Much to Ask]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Lars|first=Brandle|title=Niall Horan Drops New Single 'Too Much to Ask': Listen|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7965738/niall-horan-single-too-much-to-ask|accessdate=15 September 2017|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=15 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n''Flicker'' was released on 20 October 2017, and debuted atop the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8015056/niall-horan-flicker-debut-billboard-200-albums-chart|title=Niall Horan's 'Flicker' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> It also reached number one in Ireland and the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irma.ie/#chartTab2|title=IRMA \u2013 Irish Recorded Music Association|website=Irma.ie|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitparade.ch/showitem.asp?interpret=Niall+Horan&titel=Flicker&cat=a|title=Niall Horan - Flicker|last=Hung|first=Steffen|website=hitparade.ch|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> On 8 November 2017, he performed alongside Maren Morris at the [[51st Annual Country Music Association Awards|51st Country Music Association Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/8013872/niall-horan-perform-maren-morris-cma-awards|title=Niall Horan to Perform With Maren Morris at CMA Awards on Nov. 8|website=Billboard.com|accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref> In 2018, he embarked on the [[Flicker World Tour]] to promote the album.\n\n===2019\u2013present: ''Heartbreak Weather''===\nIn September 2019, Horan stated that he had been working on his upcoming second studio album with [[Greg Kurstin]], who helped him with a ballad entitled \"Put a Little Love on Me\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Adejobi |first=Alicia |title=Niall Horan teases Adele-style break-up ballad that's the best song he's ever written\u2019' |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/09/05/niall-horan-teases-adele-style-break-ballad-best-song-ever-written-10694991 |website=Metro |accessdate=5 September 2019 |date=5 September 2019}}</ref> The album's lead single, \"[[Nice to Meet Ya]]\", was released on 4 October 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8531472/niall-horan-announces-nice-to-meet-ya-single|title=Niall Horan Announces 'Nice to Meet Ya' Single|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Pace|first=Lilly|date=26 September 2019|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref> On 30 October, Horan announced that he would be embarking on the [[Nice to Meet Ya Tour]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8541547/niall-horan-spring-2020-north-american-tour-dates |title=Niall Horan Adds Dates to North American Tour: See When He's Coming to Your City |website=Billboard.com |date= |accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> \"[[Put a Little Love on Me]]\" was released as the album's second single on 6 December 2019.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://z100.iheart.com/content/2019-10-30-niall-horan-announces-2020-nice-to-meet-ya-arena-tour-with-lewis-capaldi/ |title=Niall Horan Announces 2020 'Nice To Meet Ya' Arena Tour With Lewis Capaldi &#124; Z100 |website=Z100.iheart.com |date=2019-10-30 |accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> On 7 February 2020, Horan released the album's third single, \"[[No Judgement]]\" alongside revealing the album's title as ''[[Heartbreak Weather]]'' and announcing 13 March 2020 as the release date.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8550391/niall-horan-no-judgement |title=Niall Horan Sets New Album 'Heartbreak Weather,' Drops New Single 'No Judgement': Listen |website=Billboard.com |date=2020-02-07 |accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\nHoran's solo debut album was described as being on the \"folkier side of pop\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/entertainment_life/article_03d3181e-b4f0-11e7-8eff-4b01aec38136.html|title=Album review: Without 1D, Niall Horan walks on the folkier side|work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]|first=Mark|last=Kennedy|date=26 October 2017|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref> incorporating elements of [[folk music]] as well as [[pop rock]], [[soft rock]], and [[country music]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Levine|first=Nick|title=Niall Horan \u2013 'Flicker' Review|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/album/niall-horan-flicker-album-review|work=[[NME]]|date=20 October 2017|accessdate=22 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/niall-horan-flicker-review-dripping-with-country-style-nostalgia-1.3259498|title=Niall Horan: Flicker review: dripping with country-style nostalgia|work=[[The Irish Times]]|first=Louise|last=Bruton|date=20 October 2017|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref> In an interview with Digital Spy, Horan cited [[Michael Bubl\u00e9]] as one of his biggest influences because they had similar life histories, as he was discovered by his aunt and the same thing happened to Bubl\u00e9, except he was discovered by his father.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tigerbeat.com/2012/11/niall-horan-meets-michael-buble/|title=Niall Horan Meets Michael Buble! {{!}} TigerBeat|work=BOP and Tiger Beat|date=7 November 2012|accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHoran has also stated that he is a \"big, big [[swing music|swing]] fan\", citing his favourite artists as [[Frank Sinatra]], [[Dean Martin]], and Bubl\u00e9.<ref name=HoranVEVO>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8kfcs3ODpPU&feature=player_embedded|title=Niall Interview (VEVO LIFT): Brought to you by McDonald's|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=16 March 2012 |accessdate=27 April 2012}}</ref> Horan likes pop and rock music and is a fan of [[Eagles (band)|The Eagles]], [[Fleetwood Mac]], [[Taylor Swift]], [[Bon Jovi]], [[The Script]], [[Take That]], and [[Westlife]].<ref name=HoranVEVO/><ref name=\"nationalpost1\">{{cite news|author=Leah Collins|url=http://arts.nationalpost.com/2012/03/12/one-direction-is-more-than-just-another-boy-band|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20120313001910/http://arts.nationalpost.com/2012/03/12/one-direction-is-more-than-just-another-boy-band/|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 March 2012|title=One Direction: X Factor boy band on what sets them apart|work=National Post|location=Canada|publisher=[[Postmedia Network]] Inc.|date=12 March 2012|accessdate=17 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Levine|first1=Nick|title=One Direction\u2019s Niall working on \u2018folk-pop\u2019 album inspired by Fleetwood Mac, The Eagles|url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/one-directions-niall-working-folk-pop-album-inspired-fleetwood-mac-eagles-1921206|work=NME|accessdate=11 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/niallofficial/status/24911387599835136|title=@ellaappleyard I'm a westlife and take that fan|first=Niall|last=Horan}}{{Primary source inline|date=July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Niall Horan says Taylor Swift is \"the dream\"!|date=June 24, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EcjRYdk8gBk|work=[[YouTube]]|publisher=[[OnDemand|On Demand Entertainment]]|language=en|access-date=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHoran enjoyed playing a number of sports while growing up, including golf, football, and [[Gaelic football]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title = Who We Are: Our Autobiography|last = Direction |first= One|publisher = Harper Collins|year = 2014|isbn = 978-0-00-757731-6|location = London|pages = 86\u2013145}}</ref> In the summer of 2010, while playing football with friends, he injured his knee and was diagnosed with a floating kneecap.<ref name=\":0\" /> The problem recurred several times over the next couple of years, including a 2013 incident where he dislocated his knee onstage during a concert in Antwerp, Belgium.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=One Direction Antwerp 1-5-13 Niall and Louis DANCE COMPETITION (Niall hurts his knee)||url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fdqEv5JwWkU|publisher=YouTube||accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref> Horan went to the United States for major reconstructive surgery in January 2014, after the tour ended.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web|title = One Direction's Niall Horan Has Major Knee Surgery|url = http://www.eonline.com/news/500586/one-direction-s-niall-horan-has-major-knee-surgery-three-months-before-where-we-are-tour-kickoff|website = E! Online|accessdate = 10 December 2015}}</ref> After the surgery, he was invited to do physical therapy with [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] by their manager, [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]]. Horan went through more than seven weeks of physical therapy with the members of the team and their physical therapist at their training ground in Surrey.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHoran is a supporter of Football League Championship side [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tyler|first1=Kelly|title=Derby County fan and One Direction star Niall Horan to hold charity football challenge|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Derby-County-fan-Direction-star-Niall-Horan-hold/story-20974570-detail/story.html|work=Derby Telegraph|accessdate=25 June 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210202011/http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/Derby-County-fan-Direction-star-Niall-Horan-hold/story-20974570-detail/story.html|archivedate=10 December 2014}}</ref> He is also a fan of golf. He can be seen at numerous golf events and has participated in the [[BMW PGA Championship]] Pro-Am at Wentworth.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jackson|first1=Keith|title=Niall Horan walks and talks with Wayne Riley during the BMW PGA pro-am|url=http://www.skysports.com/golf/news/12176/10294406/niall-horan-walks-and-talks-with-wayne-riley-during-the-bmw-pga-pro-am|work=Sky Sports|accessdate=11 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/golf/news/12176/10769806/niall-horan-and-justin-rose-team-up-for-the-genesis-open-pro-am|title=Niall Horan and Justin Rose team up for the Genesis Open Pro-Am\n|website=Sky Sports|access-date=11 April 2017}}</ref> He caddied for professional golfer [[Rory McIlroy]] for the Par 3 contest prior to the [[2015 Masters Tournament]] in Augusta, Georgia.<ref>{{cite web|title = Rory McIlroy leans on Niall Horan for par threes but his one direction is up|url = https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/apr/07/rory-mcilroy-niall-horan-one-direction-masters|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 10 December 2015}}</ref> He also expressed his support for the [[Ireland cricket team]].<ref>[http://www.beautifulballad.org/2015/01/21/niall-horan-enjoys-a-cricket-match-in-melbourne/ Niall Horan Enjoys A Cricket Match In Melbourne] beautifulballad.org. Retrieved 22 January 2016.</ref><ref>[http://www.cricketireland.ie/news/article/niall-horan-joins-growing-chorus-of-celebrities-backinggreen Niall Horan joins growing chorus of celebrities #BackingGreen] ''[[Cricket Ireland]]''. Retrieved 22 January 2016.</ref><ref>[https://twitter.com/StarsBBL/status/690486485666107392 We'd like to welcome back @NiallOfficial to the @MCG for his second @StarsBBL match] ''[[Melbourne Stars]]''. Retrieved 22 January 2016.</ref> Horan is also a [[Rugby union|rugby]] fan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/leftfield/what-is-niall-talking-about-one-direction-fans-confused-by-niall-horans-rugby-tweets-31541021.html|title='What is Niall talking about' - One Direction fans confused by Niall Horan's rugby tweets|website=Independent.ie}}</ref> He has tweeted several times in support of the [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland rugby team]] and was seen attending a [[Leinster rugby]] match with Rory McIlroy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/rugby-union/news/15180/10289586/rory-mcilroy-and-one-directions-niall-horan-at-pro12-semi-final|title=Rory McIlroy and One Direction's Niall Horan at PRO12 semi-final|website=Sky Sports}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Horan was actively involved with the Drive, Chip, and Putt initiative that encourages and supports children golfers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.modestgolf.com/profile/|title=PROFILE - Modest! Golf|work=Modest! Golf|accessdate=9 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.golfchannel.com/video/horan-drive-chip-and-putt-kids-are-inspirational/|title=Drive, Chip and Putt 2016: Niall Horan interview|website=Golf Channel|accessdate=9 May 2018}}</ref> Horan also helped promote the [[Northern Ireland Open (Challenge Tour)|Northern Ireland Open]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/golf/news/12176/11068181/niall-horan-enjoying-being-part-of-a-golf-management-team|title=Niall Horan enjoying being part of a golf management team|work=[[Sky Sports]]|accessdate=26 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Horan opened up on his diagnosis of mild [[OCD]] and his [[anxiety]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/niall-horan/speaks-openly-about-his-ocd/|title=Niall Horan Is Praised By Fans For Speaking Openly About His Struggles With OCD|work=Capital|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/niall-horan-said-he-has-mild-obsessive-compulsive-disorder|title=Niall Horan Said He Has \"Mild\" Obsessive Compulsive Disorder|work=Teen Vogue|last=Rearick|first=Lauren|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\n[[File:Niallcharityfootball6 (cropped 2).jpg|thumb|right|180px|Horan during his Charity Football Challenge at [[King Power Stadium]] in May 2014]]\nAs a former member of One Direction, Horan was involved in the Action 1D campaign that \"aims to end extreme poverty, tackle inequality and slow down [[climate change]] with the help of their millions of fans\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/one-direction/news/one-direction-launch-action-1d-campaign-to-raise-awareness-of-global-issues|title=One Direction Launch Action 1D Campaign To Raise Awareness Of Global Issues {{!}} MTV UK|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref> The band also supported [[Comic Relief]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.comicrelief.com/news/one-direction-raises-over-%C2%A32-million-red-nose-day-2013|title=One Direction raises over \u00a32 million for Red Nose Day 2013 {{!}} Comic Relief|work=Comic Relief|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, Horan hosted the Charity Football Challenge at [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]'s [[King Power Stadium]] to raise money for Irish Autism Action. The celebrity football match had 10,000 spectators and raised about \u00a3300,000 for the charity.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.itv.com/news/central/story/2014-05-26/one-direction-heartthrobs-in-leicester-for-nialls-charity-football-challenge/ |title=One Direction heartthrobs in Leicester for Niall's charity football challenge - ITV News |website=Itv.com |date=2014-05-26 |accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> In 2016, Horan continued to support Irish Autism Action by creating limited edition T-shirts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.m-magazine.com/posts/niall-horan-designs-his-own-t-shirt-for-charity-102792|title=Niall Horan Designs His Own T-Shirt For Charity|work=M Magazine|date=20 May 2016|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHoran teamed up with ''[[Golf Digest]]'' to raise money for the REACH military families.<ref>{{Citation|last=Golf Digest|title=Niall Horan Talks Taylor Swift, In & Out Burger, & Golf with Bill Murray {{!}} Golf Digest|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rrJvOjeILUw|date=3 March 2017|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref> Horan and golf player [[Justin Rose]] created the \"Horan and Rose Gala\", a charity event in aid of Cancer Research UK Kids and Teens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sugarscape.com/lads/news/a1087867/niall-horan-justin-rose-charity-gala/|title=Niall Horan's hosting a charity gala with golfer fella Justin Rose|date=21 March 2016|website=Sugarscape|access-date=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHoran was announced to be joining the [[Soccer Aid]] 2016 star lineup fundraiser for [[UNICEF]] as an assistant manager and player for the Rest of the World team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unicef.org.uk/Media-centre/Press-releases/One-Directions-Niall-Horan-goes-head-to-head-with-band-mate-Louis-Tomlinson-for-Soccer-Aid-2016/|title=One Direction's Niall Horan signs up for Soccer Aid 2016 {{!}} Press Releases|website=Unicef.org.uk|access-date=20 May 2016}}</ref> In 2017, Horan received an Arnie Award for his work with charities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.golfdigest.com/story/niall-horan-gets-our-arnie-award-and-helps-guide-the-games-talent|title=Niall Horan Gets Our Arnie Award And Helps Guide The Game's Talent \u2013 Golf Digest|last1=Furore|first1=Dom|last2=Wacker|first2=Brian|work=Golf Digest|accessdate=22 April 2018}}</ref> In 2019, Horan joins UNICEF's Soccer Aid World XI team, formerly called Rest of the World, alongside retired sprinter Usain Bolt and former Chelsea FC player Didier Drogba. UNICEF's soccer aid tournament aims to raise funds to benefit children around the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/niall-horan-joins-soccer-aids-world-xi-team-37985141.html|title=Niall Horan joins Soccer Aid\u2019s World XI team|accessdate=5 April 2019|website=Independent.ie}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[iCarly]]''\n| rowspan=\"4\"| Himself\n|Episode: \"[[List of iCarly episodes#ep86|iGo One Direction]]\"\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[One Direction: This Is Us]]''\n| [[Documentary]] concert film\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[One Direction: Where We Are \u2013 The Concert Film]]''\n| [[Concert film]]\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[One Love Manchester]]''\n| Television special\n|-\n