an-awards-honoured-canadas-best-class |title=29th Annual SOCAN Awards Honoured Canada's Best In Class |date=19 June 2018 |first=Kerry |last=Doole |work=Fyi Music News|accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Teen Choice Awards]] \n| Choice Male Artist \n|rowspan=2|Niall Horan \n|rowspan=3 {{nominated}} \n|rowspan=\"3\"| <ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8469754/teen-choice-awards-winners-list-2018 |title=Teen Choice Awards Winners 2018: See the Full List (Updating Live) |date=12 August 2018 |first=Ashley |last=Iasimone |work=Billboard |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|Choice Summer Male Artist\n|-\n|Choice Summer Tour\n|[[Flicker World Tour]] \n|-\n|[[BMI Awards|BMI London Awards]]\n|Pop Award Songs\n|\"Slow Hands\"\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bmi.com/news/entry/2018-bmi-london-awards |title=Harry Gregson-Williams and Other Top Songwriters Honored At 2018 BMI London Awards |work=BMI |accessdate=8 October 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Hollywood Music in Media Awards]] \n|Original Song \u2013 Animated Film\n|\"[[Smallfoot (film)|Finally Free]]\"\n| rowspan=3 {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hmmawards.com/2018-music-in-visual-media-nominations |title=Complete list of 2018 HMMA Music In Visual Media Nominations |work=Hollywood Music in Media Awards |accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=4| 2019\n|[[iHeartRadio Music Awards]]\n|Best Cover Song\n|\"[[Crying in the Club]]\"\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iheart.com/content/2019-01-09-2019-iheartradio-music-awards-see-the-full-list-of-nominees/|title=2019 iHeartRadio Music Awards: See The Full List of Nominees|publisher=[[iHeartRadio]]|date=9 January 2019|accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Teen Choice Awards]]\n|Choice Collaboration\n|\"[[What a Time]]\"\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/8516707/2019-teen-choice-awards-nominations|title=Lil Nas X & Post Malone Lead 2019 Teen Choice Awards Nominations: See the List|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=19 June 2019|accessdate=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[BMI Awards|BMI London Awards]]\n|Pop Award Songs\n|\"[[On the Loose (song)|On the Loose]]\"\n| rowspan=2 {{won}}\n|<ref name=\"billboard1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8533723/bmi-london-awards-2019-winners|title=BMI London Awards Honor Noel Gallagher, Camila Cabello, Niall Horan & More|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=22 October 2019|accessdate=24 October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[BMI Awards|BMI London Awards]]\n|Pop Award Songs\n|\"[[Too Much to Ask]]\"\n|<ref name=\"billboard1\"/>\n|}\n\n==Tours==\n{{see also|One Direction#Tours}}\n'''Headlining'''\n* [[Flicker World Tour]] (2018)\n* [[Nice to Meet Ya Tour]] (2020)\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-3}}\n'''Promotional tours'''\n* [[Flicker Sessions 2017|Flicker Sessions]] (2017)\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Billboard Social 50 number-one artists]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Niall Horan}}\n*[http://www.niallhoran.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Niall Horan}}\n{{One Direction}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Horan, Niall}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish singers]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records artists]]\n[[Category:Folk-pop singers]]\n[[Category:Irish guitarists]]\n[[Category:Irish male singers]]\n[[Category:Irish pop singers]]\n[[Category:Irish singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:One Direction members]]\n[[Category:People from Mullingar]]\n[[Category:Pop rock singers]]\n", "name_user": "Bombeditztttttt", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(It\u2019s was facts okay)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niall_Horan"}
{"title_page": "Sharon Moalem", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n|image        = Dr. Sharon Moalem in Tokyo, Japan.jpg\n|name         = Sharon Moalem\n|pseudonym    =\n|birth_date   = \n|birth_place  = [[Montr\u00e9al]], [[Canada]]\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  =\n|occupation   = [[Physician]], [[Scientist]], [[Author]]\n|alma_mater   = [[University of Guelph]]<br>[[University of Toronto]] <br> [[Mount Sinai School of Medicine]]\n|genre        = [[Nonfiction]]\n|movement     =\n|notableworks = ''[[Survival of the Sickest (book)|Survival of the Sickest]]'' <br> ''How Sex Works'' <br> ''Inheritance''      | website     = {{URL|sharonmoalem.com}}\n}}\n'''Sharon Moalem''' is an American [[physician]], [[scientist]], and [[Author|bestselling author]].<ref name=nyt>{{cite web|last=Blakeslee|first=Sandra|title=New Theory Places Origin of Diabetes in an Age of Icy Hardships|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/17/health/17diab.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|work=New York Times}}</ref><ref name=dailyshow>{{cite web|last=Stewart|first=Jon|title=Dr. Sharon Moalem|url=http://www.thedailyshow.com/watch/thu-march-8-2007/dr--sharon-moalem|publisher=The Daily Show}}</ref> Dr. Moalem is an expert in the fields of [[rare diseases]], [[sex differentiation]], [[neurogenetics]], [[biotechnology]] and has been described as a polymath.<ref name=sundaytimes>{{cite news |last1=Appleyard |first1=Bryan |title=Dr Sharon Moalem: why women are the genetically stronger sex |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/dr-sharon-moalem-why-women-are-the-genetically-stronger-sex-zh2xlbvt8 |publisher=The Sunday Times}}</ref><ref name=today>{{cite web|title=Why we need disease|url=http://www.today.com/id/17008658/ns/today-books/t/why-we-need-disease/#.Usy0DGRDtvZ|publisher=Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Velasquez-Manoff |first1=Moises |title=Gene Persuasion |journal=Scientific American |date=May 1, 2014 |volume=25 |issue=3 |page=72 |doi=10.1038/scientificamericanmind0514-72b}}</ref><ref name=sox3>{{cite journal |last1=Moalem S, Babul-Hirji R, Stavropolous DJ, Wherrett D, B\u00e4gli DJ, Thomas P, Chitayat D |title=XX male sex reversal with genital abnormalities associated with a de novo SOX3 gene duplication. |journal=American Journal of Medical Genetics |date=2012 |volume=158 |issue=7 |pages=1759\u201364 |doi=10.1002/ajmg.a.35390 |pmid=22678921}}</ref> He is the author of the ''New York Times'' bestselling book ''[[Survival of the Sickest (book)|Survival of the Sickest,]]'' as well as ''[[How Sex Works]]'' and ''Inheritance''.<ref name=time>{{cite web|last=Cruz|first=Gilbert|title=How Sex Works|url=http://content.time.com/time/health/article/0,8599,1895544,00.html|publisher=Time}}</ref><ref name=wp>{{cite web|last=Harris|first=Lynn|title=Lynn Harris Reviews 'Behind the Bedroom Door,' 'How Sex Works,'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/21/AR2009072102755.html|work=Washington Post}}</ref> His clinical genetics research led to the discovery of three rare genetic syndromes, [[hypotrichosis]]-[[lymphedema]]-[[telangiectasia]]-[[renal]] defect syndrome, and a form of XX male sex reversal as well as a nephronopthisis associated ciliopathy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hypotrichosis-Lymphedema-Telangiectasia-Renal Defect Syndrome |url=https://disorders.eyes.arizona.edu/disorders/hypotrichosis-lymphedema-telangiectasia-renal-defect-syndrome |publisher=The University of Arizona Health Sciences}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Moalem S, Brouillard P, Kuypers D, Legius E, Harvey E, Taylor G, Francois M, Vikkula M, Chitayat D. |title=Hypotrichosis-lymphedema-telangiectasia-renal defect associated with a truncating mutation in the SOX18 gene. |journal=Clinical Genetics |date=2015 |volume=87 |issue=4 |pages=378\u201382 |doi=10.1111/cge.12388 |pmid=24697860}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Robb |first1=Peter |title=Genetic science is transforming health care and introducing ethical dilemmas |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/entertainment/books/genetic-science-is-transforming-health-care-and-introducing-ethical-dilemmas |publisher=Ottawa Citizen}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ripped Genes: Let's Talk Orphan Diseases |url=https://medium.com/@flatworldx/ripped-genes-bac49a025d3f |website=Medium}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Human Disease Database |title=Hypotrichosis-Lymphedema-Telangiectasia-Renal Defect Syndrome |url=https://www.malacards.org/card/hypotrichosis_lymphedema_telangiectasia_renal_defect_syndrome}}</ref> Moalem has cofounded two [[Biotechnology company|biotechnology companies]] and has been awarded 25 patents for his inventions in biotechnology and human health.<ref name=dailyshow/><ref name=today/><ref name=linked>{{cite web|title=Sharon Moalem|url=http://www.linkedin.com/in/drsharonmoalem|publisher=LinkedIn}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Shank |first1=David |title=The Genius in All of Us |url=https://www.writersvoice.net/2014/06/dr-sharon-moalem-inheritance-david-shenk-the-genius-in-all-of-us/ |publisher=Apple Podcasts}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMoalem earned his [[Doctor of Philosophy]] in [[Human Physiology]] specializing in [[Neurogenetics]] from the [[University of Toronto]].<ref name=oprah>{{cite web|last=Oz|first=Mehmet|title=The Benefits of Disease|url=http://www.oprah.com/health/The-Benefits-of-Disease|publisher=Oprah}}</ref> He completed his [[Doctor of Medicine]] at [[Mount Sinai School of Medicine]] in [[New York City]]. As a college student, Dr. Moalem worked with the King of Thailand [[Bhumibol Adulyadej]] to help improve the care of young children at an [[HIV-positive]] [[orphanage]].<ref name=CPBN>{{cite web|title=Featured Profile: Dr. Sharon Moalem|url=http://www.cpbn.org/profile/dr-sharon-moalem|publisher=CPBN|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202120705/http://www.cpbn.org/profile/dr-sharon-moalem|archivedate=2014-02-02}}</ref>  In this capacity Dr. Moalem worked in HIV prevention for the [[Population and Community Development Association]] (PDA) and was responsible for the operations of the Tarn Nam Jai HIV+ Orphanage in [[Bangkok, Thailand]].<ref name=CPBN/>\n\nHis research in [[neurogenetics]] led to the discovery of new genetic associations for familial [[Alzheimer's disease]].<ref name=dailyshow/><ref name=time/> He was previously the Associate Editor of the Journal of Alzheimer's Disease.<ref name=linked/> Dr. Moalem's scientific work, based upon using rare conditions as a template to understand more common conditions, led to the discovery of Siderocillin a new antibiotic that specifically targets so called \u2018[[super bug (bacteria)|superbugs]]\u2019 or multiresistant microbes.<ref name=dailyshow/><ref name=linked/><ref name=Amazon>{{cite web|title=Profile: Sharon Moalem|url=https://www.amazon.com/Sharon-Moalem/e/B001JRUZVW|publisher=Amazon}}</ref>\n\nMoalem was the lead author on the paper that first described the condition [[hypotrichosis]]-[[lymphedema]]-[[telangiectasia]]-[[renal]] defect syndrome (HLTRS) that resulted from a [[heterozygous]] mutation in the [[SOX18]] gene.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Moalem S, Brouillard P, Kuypers D, Legius E, Harvey E, Taylor G, Francois M, Vikkula M, Chitayat D. |title=Hypotrichosis-lymphedema-telangiectasia-renal defect associated with a truncating mutation in the SOX18 gene. |journal=Clinical Genetics |date=2015 |volume=87 |issue=4 |pages=378\u201382 |doi=10.1111/cge.12388 |pmid=24697860}}</ref> The SOX18 gene has a major role in the formation of blood and lymphatic vessels but prior to the description of HLTRS was not understood to be involved in renal function. His clinical research also led to the description of an SRY negative type of XX male sex reversal that resulted from a duplication of the [[SOX3]] gene found on the X chromosome.<ref name=sox3/> The SOX3 gene encodes a protein that is similar but distinct to the [[testis-determining factor]] (TDF), also known as sex-determining region Y (SRY) protein that is found on the [[Y chromosome]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Waters PD, Wallis MC, Marshall Graves JA. |title=Mammalian sex--Origin and evolution of the Y chromosome and SRY. |journal=Seminars in Cell and Developmental Biology |date=2007 |volume=18 |issue=3 |pages=389\u2013400 |doi=10.1016/j.semcdb.2007.02.007 |pmid=17400006}}</ref> \n\nHe has founded two [[Biotechnology company|biotechnology companies]], Sideromics LLC and Recognyz System Technology, founded to develop treatments for the health effects experiences by persons with rare diseases.<ref name=men>{{cite web|title=Sharon Moalem|url=http://www.mendeley.com/profiles/sharon-moalem/|publisher=Mendeley}}</ref><ref name=linked/> Moalem has also been awarded 25 patents for inventions related to biotechnology and human health.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Essert |first1=Matt |title=This App Will Soon Detect Your Genetic Diseases \u2014 Based Only on a Picture |url=https://www.mic.com/articles/83269/this-app-will-soon-detect-your-genetic-diseases-based-only-on-a-picture |publisher=MIC}}</ref><ref name=linked/>\n\nIn March 2014, Dr. Moalem and his team won a [[hackathon]] at [[MIT]] to build a [[smartphone app]] that can be used to treat patients by identifying predispositions to certain diseases based on facial structure.<ref name=businessinsider>{{cite web|last=Love|first=Dylan|title=A Doctor Is Building A Powerful Smartphone App That 'Can Tell You If Your Mother Drank While She Was Pregnant With You'|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/sharon-moalem-hacking-medicine-smartphone-app-2014-2|publisher=Business Insider}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=App to use facial recognition to spot medical conditions |journal=Biometric Technology Today |volume=2014 |issue=4 |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0969476514700621}}</ref>\n\nDr. Moalem has been described as a polymath.<ref name=sundaytimes></ref> He is a frequent [[keynote speaker]] on the topics of [[genetics]], [[pandemics]], [[evolution]], [[antimicrobial resistance]], [[iron]] metabolism, [[botany]], [[entomology]], [[personalized medicine]] and has appeared on [[NBC]]'s [[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today Show]], [[BBC Radio London]], [[Bloomberg Television]], [[CNN]], [[Comedy Central]]'s [[The Daily Show with Jon Stewart]], [[CBS This Morning]], [[Good Morning America]] and [[NPR]].<ref name=dailyshow/><ref name=today/><ref name=speak>{{cite web|title=Dr. Sharon Moalem|url=http://www.harpercollinsspeakersbureau.com/speaker/dr-sharon-moalem/|publisher=Harper Collins Speaker Bureau}}</ref><ref name=npr>{{cite web|last=Rehm|first=Diane|title=Sharon Moalem: \"Survival of the Sickest\"|url=http://thedianerehmshow.org/shows/2007-02-26/sharon-moalem-survival-sickest-william-morrow|publisher=The Diane Rehm Show}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Thursday's TV Highlights |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-thursdays-tv-highlights-the-crazy-ones-on-cbs-20140409-story.html |website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n===''Survival of the Sickest: A medical maverick discovers why we need disease''===\nDr. Moalem's first book ''[[Survival of the Sickest (book)|Survival of the Sickest]]'' was published in 2007 by [[William Morrow (publisher)|William Morrow]] (HarperCollins). The book, co-written by Jonathan Prince, lays out eight case studies revolving around the argument that common hereditary diseases exist because at one point they were an adaptive advantage for our ancestors.<ref name=today/> One proposed hypothesis is that water induced wrinkling of skin is an adaptation to improve traction in wet or slippery environments. Research has subsequently shown this to be likely the case.<ref>{{cite web|title=Water-induced finger wrinkles improve handling of wet objects|url=http://rsbl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/9/2/20120999|publisher=Royal Society Publishing}}</ref><ref name=nyt/><ref name=Patheos>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Adam|title=Book Review: Survival of the Sickest|url=http://www.patheos.com/blogs/daylightatheism/2007/03/survival-of-the-sickest/|publisher=Patheos}}</ref>\n\nThe book debuted on the ''New York Time''s bestselling book list in hardcover nonfiction.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hardcover Nonfiction|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/04/books/bestseller/0304besthardnonfiction.html?_r=0|work=New York Times}}</ref>\n\n===''How Sex Works:  Why We Look, Smell, Taste, Feel, and Act the Way We Do''===\nIn April 2009, Dr. Moalem's second book ''How Sex Works: Why We Look, Smell, Taste, Feel, and Act the Way We Do'' was published by [[HarperCollins]].<ref name=oprah2>{{cite web|last=Winter|first=Jessica|title=Between the Covers|url=http://www.oprah.com/omagazine/How-Sex-Works-by-Sharon-Moalem-Book-Review|publisher=Oprah}}</ref> The book examines the scientific reasons why people are attracted to one another.<ref name=time/> The topics covered include the evolutionary underpinnings of [[sexual attraction]], [[monogamy]], and [[sexual orientation]].<ref name=abc>{{cite web|title=EXCERPT: 'How Sex Works'|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/Books/story?id=7472408|publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref name=wp/><ref name=tbt>{{cite web|last=Miller|first=Jen A.|title=Review: 'How Sex Works: Why We Look, Smell, Taste, Feel, and Act the Way We Do,' by Dr. Sharon Moalem|url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/health/review-how-sex-works-why-we-look-smell-taste-feel-and-act-the-way-we-do/1003125|publisher=Tampa Bay Times|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202122205/http://www.tampabay.com/news/health/review-how-sex-works-why-we-look-smell-taste-feel-and-act-the-way-we-do/1003125|archivedate=2014-02-02}}</ref>\n\n===''Inheritance:  How Our Genes Change Our Lives\u2014And Our Lives Change Our Genes''===\nIn April 2014, ''Inheritance'' was published by Grand Central Publishing.<ref>{{cite web |title=Inheritance by Sharon Moalem MD, PhD |url=https://www.grandcentralpublishing.com/titles/sharon-moalem-md-phd/inheritance/9781455549450/ |website=Grand Central Publishing}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Velasquez-Manoff |first1=Moises |title=MIND Reviews: Inheritance |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/mind-reviews-inheritance/ |publisher=Scientific American}}</ref> The book, co-written by journalist Matthew D. LaPlante, unpacks emerging research into the flexible genome, which is \"mediated and orchestrated by how you live, where you live, the stresses you face, and the things you consume,\u201d promising a future in which people will make health decisions not based on what is good for most of the people most of the time, but rather what is genetically best for each individual based on their specific genetic and epigenetic profile. Inheritance was named one of Amazon's Best Science Books of 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leopold |first1=Todd |title=Amazon picks the 100 best books of 2014 |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2014/11/10/living/amazon-100-best-books-2014-ng/index.html |publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\n===''The Better Half: On the Genetic Superiority of Women''===\n\n''The Better Half'' was published in April 2020 by [[Farrar, Straus and Giroux]] and by [[Allen Lane]] (an imprint of [[Penguin Books]]) in the United Kingdom.<ref name=sundaytimes></ref> Prior to publication, ''The Better Half'' was named one of the non-fiction books to look out for in 2020 by the ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]], [[Evening Standard]]'' and the ''[[Sunday Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hampson |first1=Laura |title=World Book Day: the best books to look forward to in 2020 |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/books/best-books-coming-out-in-2020-a4324796.html |publisher=Evening Standard}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Holgate |first1=Andrew |title=The Sunday Times books to watch out for in 2020 |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/2020-what-to-watch-out-for-next-year-sunday-times-books-gb2dwht8s |publisher=The Sunday Times}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sharkey |first1=Lauren |title=9 Investigative Non-Fiction Books To Sink Your Teeth Into In 2020 |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/9-investigative-non-fiction-books-to-sink-your-teeth-into-in-2020-21735801 |publisher=Bustle}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2020 in books |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/jan/04/2020-in-books-a-literary-calendar |publisher=The Guardian}}</ref> In the book Moalem argues that from birth, genetic females possess a survival advantage that results from them being the [[homogametic]] sex that have inherited two X chromosomes, as opposed to genetic males who are the [[heterogametic]] sex with one X and Y chromosome.<ref name=sundaytimes></ref> Moalem explains that not only do genetic females have more genetic information than males, but that female cells using different X chromosomes can interact and cooperate, which gives them an advantage throughout the life course and especially in times of [[famine]] and [[pandemic]]s.<ref name=newstatesman>{{cite web |last1=Bootle |first1=Emily |title=The female of the species is more healthy than the male Physician Sharon Moalem on the role our sex chromosomes play in immunity and genetic advantage. |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/health/2020/04/female-species-more-healthy-male |website=New Statesman}}</ref> Moalem's assertion regarding the female survival advantage became apparent during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], where males were found to have a higher mortality rate reported across many age groups.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moalem |first1=Sharon |title=Why Are So Many More Men Dying from Coronavirus? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/opinion/coronavirus-men-women.html |publisher=The New York Times |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Schumaker |first1=Erin |title=COVID-19 mortality twice as high for men in Italy as women |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/covid-19-mortality-high-men-italy-women/story?id=69717021 |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ahuja |first1=Anjana |title=When it comes to coronavirus, men are more vulnerable  Differences in immune function appear to start straight out of the womb |url=https://www.ft.com/content/a32e62b4-4be9-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 |publisher=Financial Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Devlin |first1=Hannah |title=Men are much more likely to die from coronavirus - but why? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/men-are-much-more-likely-to-die-from-coronavirus-but-why |publisher=The Guardian |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rabin |first1=Roni Caryn |title=In Italy, Coronavirus Takes a Higher Toll on Men |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/20/health/coronavirus-italy-men-risk.html |publisher=The New York Times |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The book also explicates that female immunological superiority is rooted in them being the homogametic sex as well as being aided by the fact that [[estrogens]] are thought to be able to stimulate the immune system, while [[androgens]] such as testosterone have been found to suppress the immune system of males.<ref name=sundaytimes></ref> Moalem further explicates that the result of the more robust immune system that females posses provides an explanation for the much higher rate of [[autoimmune disorders]] observed in females.<ref name=newstatesman></ref> In the final chapter of the book, Moalem argues why sex chromosomes matter in medicine as he calls for a long-overdue reconsideration of our male-centric, one-size-fits-all view of the body, a view that even today continues to frame women through the lens of men.<ref name=sundaytimes></ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://sharonmoalem.com\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moalem, Sharon}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American geneticists]]\n[[Category:University of Toronto alumni]]\n[[Category:Mount Sinai School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish physicians]]\n[[Category:American physicians]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n|image        = Dr. Sharon Moalem in Tokyo, Japan.jpg\n|name         = Sharon Moalem\n|pseudonym    =\n|birth_date   = \n|birth_place  = [[Montr\u00e9al]], [[Canada]]\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  =\n|occupation   = [[Physician]], [[Scientist]], [[Author]]\n|alma_mater   = [[University of Guelph]]<br>[[University of Toronto]] <br> [[Mount Sinai School of Medicine]]\n|genre        = [[Nonfiction]]\n|movement     =\n|notableworks = ''[[Survival of the Sickest (book)|Survival of the Sickest]]'' <br> ''How Sex Works'' <br> ''Inheritance''      | website     = {{URL|sharonmoalem.com}}\n}}\n'''Sharon Moalem''' is an American [[physician]], [[scientist]], and [[Author|bestselling author]].<ref name=nyt>{{cite web|last=Blakeslee|first=Sandra|title=New Theory Places Origin of Diabetes in an Age of Icy Hardships|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/17/health/17diab.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|work=New York Times}}</ref><ref name=dailyshow>{{cite web|last=Stewart|first=Jon|title=Dr. Sharon Moalem|url=http://www.thedailyshow.com/watch/thu-march-8-2007/dr--sharon-moalem|publisher=The Daily Show}}</ref> Dr. Moalem is an expert in the fields of [[rare diseases]], [[sex differentiation]], [[neurogenetics]], [[biotechnology]] and has been described as a polymath.<ref name=sundaytimes>{{cite news |last1=Appleyard |first1=Bryan |title=Dr Sharon Moalem: why women are the genetically stronger sex |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/dr-sharon-moalem-why-women-are-the-genetically-stronger-sex-zh2xlbvt8 |publisher=The Sunday Times}}</ref><ref name=today>{{cite web|title=Why we need disease|url=http://www.today.com/id/17008658/ns/today-books/t/why-we-need-disease/#.Usy0DGRDtvZ|publisher=Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Velasquez-Manoff |first1=Moises |title=Gene Persuasion |journal=Scientific American |date=May 1, 2014 |volume=25 |issue=3 |page=72 |doi=10.1038/scientificamericanmind0514-72b}}</ref><ref name=sox3>{{cite journal |last1=Moalem S, Babul-Hirji R, Stavropolous DJ, Wherrett D, B\u00e4gli DJ, Thomas P, Chitayat D |title=XX male sex reversal with genital abnormalities associated with a de novo SOX3 gene duplication. |journal=American Journal of Medical Genetics |date=2012 |volume=158 |issue=7 |pages=1759\u201364 |doi=10.1002/ajmg.a.35390 |pmid=22678921}}</ref> He is the author of the ''New York Times'' bestselling book ''[[Survival of the Sickest (book)|Survival of the Sickest,]]'' as well as ''[[How Sex Works]]'' and ''Inheritance''.<ref name=time>{{cite web|last=Cruz|first=Gilbert|title=How Sex Works|url=http://content.time.com/time/health/article/0,8599,1895544,00.html|publisher=Time}}</ref><ref name=wp>{{cite web|last=Harris|first=Lynn|title=Lynn Harris Reviews 'Behind the Bedroom Door,' 'How Sex Works,'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/21/AR2009072102755.html|work=Washington Post}}</ref> His clinical genetics research led to the discovery of three rare genetic syndromes, [[hypotrichosis]]-[[lymphedema]]-[[telangiectasia]]-[[renal]] defect syndrome, and a form of XX male sex reversal as well as a nephronopthisis associated ciliopathy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hypotrichosis-Lymphedema-Telangiectasia-Renal Defect Syndrome |url=https://disorders.eyes.arizona.edu/disorders/hypotrichosis-lymphedema-telangiectasia-renal-defect-syndrome |publisher=The University of Arizona Health Sciences}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Moalem S, Brouillard P, Kuypers D, Legius E, Harvey E, Taylor G, Francois M, Vikkula M, Chitayat D. |title=Hypotrichosis-lymphedema-telangiectasia-renal defect associated with a truncating mutation in the SOX18 gene. |journal=Clinical Genetics |date=2015 |volume=87 |issue=4 |pages=378\u201382 |doi=10.1111/cge.12388 |pmid=24697860}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Robb |first1=Peter |title=Genetic science is transforming health care and introducing ethical dilemmas |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/entertainment/books/genetic-science-is-transforming-health-care-and-introducing-ethical-dilemmas |publisher=Ottawa Citizen}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ripped Genes: Let's Talk Orphan Diseases |url=https://medium.com/@flatworldx/ripped-genes-bac49a025d3f |website=Medium}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Human Disease Database |title=Hypotrichosis-Lymphedema-Telangiectasia-Renal Defect Syndrome |url=https://www.malacards.org/card/hypotrichosis_lymphedema_telangiectasia_renal_defect_syndrome}}</ref> Moalem has cofounded two [[Biotechnology company|biotechnology companies]] and has been awarded 25 patents for his inventions in biotechnology and human health.<ref name=dailyshow/><ref name=today/><ref name=linked>{{cite web|title=Sharon Moalem|url=http://www.linkedin.com/in/drsharonmoalem|publisher=LinkedIn}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Shank |first1=David |title=The Genius in All of Us |url=https://www.writersvoice.net/2014/06/dr-sharon-moalem-inheritance-david-shenk-the-genius-in-all-of-us/ |publisher=Apple Podcasts}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMoalem earned his [[Doctor of Philosophy]] in [[Human Physiology]] specializing in [[Neurogenetics]] from the [[University of Toronto]].<ref name=oprah>{{cite web|last=Oz|first=Mehmet|title=The Benefits of Disease|url=http://www.oprah.com/health/The-Benefits-of-Disease|publisher=Oprah}}</ref> He completed his [[Doctor of Medicine]] at [[Mount Sinai School of Medicine]] in [[New York City]]. As a college student, Dr. Moalem worked with the King of Thailand [[Bhumibol Adulyadej]] to help improve the care of young children at an [[HIV-positive]] [[orphanage]].<ref name=CPBN>{{cite web|title=Featured Profile: Dr. Sharon Moalem|url=http://www.cpbn.org/profile/dr-sharon-moalem|publisher=CPBN|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202120705/http://www.cpbn.org/profile/dr-sharon-moalem|archivedate=2014-02-02}}</ref>  In this capacity Dr. Moalem worked in HIV prevention for the [[Population and Community Development Association]] (PDA) and was responsible for the operations of the Tarn Nam Jai HIV+ Orphanage in [[Bangkok, Thailand]].<ref name=CPBN/>\n\nHis research in [[neurogenetics]] led to the discovery of new genetic associations for familial [[Alzheimer's disease]].<ref name=dailyshow/><ref name=time/> He was previously the Associate Editor of the Journal of Alzheimer's Disease.<ref name=linked/> Dr. Moalem's scientific work, based upon using rare conditions as a template to understand more common conditions, led to the discovery of Siderocillin a new antibiotic that specifically targets so called \u2018[[super bug (bacteria)|superbugs]]\u2019 or multiresistant microbes.<ref name=dailyshow/><ref name=linked/><ref name=Amazon>{{cite web|title=Profile: Sharon Moalem|url=https://www.amazon.com/Sharon-Moalem/e/B001JRUZVW|publisher=Amazon}}</ref>\n\nMoalem was the lead author on the paper that first described the condition [[hypotrichosis]]-[[lymphedema]]-[[telangiectasia]]-[[renal]] defect syndrome (HLTRS) that resulted from a [[heterozygous]] mutation in the [[SOX18]] gene.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Moalem S, Brouillard P, Kuypers D, Legius E, Harvey E, Taylor G, Francois M, Vikkula M, Chitayat D. |title=Hypotrichosis-lymphedema-telangiectasia-renal defect associated with a truncating mutation in the SOX18 gene. |journal=Clinical Genetics |date=2015 |volume=87 |issue=4 |pages=378\u201382 |doi=10.1111/cge.12388 |pmid=24697860}}</ref> The SOX18 gene has a major role in the formation of blood and lymphatic vessels but prior to the description of HLTRS was not understood to be involved in renal function. His clinical research also led to the description of an SRY negative type of XX male sex reversal that resulted from a duplication of the [[SOX3]] gene found on the X chromosome.<ref name=sox3/> The SOX3 gene encodes a protein that is similar but distinct to the [[testis-determining factor]] (TDF), also known as sex-determining region Y (SRY) protein that is found on the [[Y chromosome]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Waters PD, Wallis MC, Marshall Graves JA. |title=Mammalian sex--Origin and evolution of the Y chromosome and SRY. |journal=Seminars in Cell and Developmental Biology |date=2007 |volume=18 |issue=3 |pages=389\u2013400 |doi=10.1016/j.semcdb.2007.02.007 |pmid=17400006}}</ref> \n\nHe has founded two [[Biotechnology company|biotechnology companies]], Sideromics LLC and Recognyz System Technology, founded to develop treatments for the health effects experiences by persons with rare diseases.<ref name=men>{{cite web|title=Sharon Moalem|url=http://www.mendeley.com/profiles/sharon-moalem/|publisher=Mendeley}}</ref><ref name=linked/> Moalem has also been awarded 25 patents for inventions related to biotechnology and human health.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Essert |first1=Matt |title=This App Will Soon Detect Your Genetic Diseases \u2014 Based Only on a Picture |url=https://www.mic.com/articles/83269/this-app-will-soon-detect-your-genetic-diseases-based-only-on-a-picture |publisher=MIC}}</ref><ref name=linked/>\n\nIn March 2014, Dr. Moalem and his team won a [[hackathon]] at [[MIT]] to build a [[smartphone app]] that can be used to treat patients by identifying predispositions to certain diseases based on facial structure.<ref name=businessinsider>{{cite web|last=Love|first=Dylan|title=A Doctor Is Building A Powerful Smartphone App That 'Can Tell You If Your Mother Drank While She Was Pregnant With You'|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/sharon-moalem-hacking-medicine-smartphone-app-2014-2|publisher=Business Insider}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=App to use facial recognition to spot medical conditions |journal=Biometric Technology Today |volume=2014 |issue=4 |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0969476514700621}}</ref>\n\nDr. Moalem has been described as a polymath.<ref name=sundaytimes></ref> He is a frequent [[keynote speaker]] on the topics of [[genetics]], [[pandemics]], [[evolution]], [[antimicrobial resistance]], [[iron]] metabolism, [[botany]], [[entomology]], [[personalized medicine]] and has appeared on [[NBC]]'s [[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today Show]], [[BBC Radio London]], [[Bloomberg Television]], [[CNN]], [[Comedy Central]]'s [[The Daily Show with Jon Stewart]], [[CBS This Morning]], [[Good Morning America]] and [[NPR]].<ref name=dailyshow/><ref name=today/><ref name=speak>{{cite web|title=Dr. Sharon Moalem|url=http://www.harpercollinsspeakersbureau.com/speaker/dr-sharon-moalem/|publisher=Harper Collins Speaker Bureau}}</ref><ref name=npr>{{cite web|last=Rehm|first=Diane|title=Sharon Moalem: \"Survival of the Sickest\"|url=http://thedianerehmshow.org/shows/2007-02-26/sharon-moalem-survival-sickest-william-morrow|publisher=The Diane Rehm Show}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Thursday's TV Highlights |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-thursdays-tv-highlights-the-crazy-ones-on-cbs-20140409-story.html |website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n===''Survival of the Sickest: A medical maverick discovers why we need disease''===\nDr. Moalem's first book ''[[Survival of the Sickest (book)|Survival of the Sickest]]'' was published in 2007 by [[William Morrow (publisher)|William Morrow]] (HarperCollins). The book, co-written by Jonathan Prince, lays out eight case studies revolving around the argument that common hereditary diseases exist because at one point they were an adaptive advantage for our ancestors.<ref name=today/> One proposed hypothesis is that water induced wrinkling of skin is an adaptation to improve traction in wet or slippery environments. Research has subsequently shown this to be likely the case.<ref>{{cite web|title=Water-induced finger wrinkles improve handling of wet objects|url=http://rsbl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/9/2/20120999|publisher=Royal Society Publishing}}</ref><ref name=nyt/><ref name=Patheos>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Adam|title=Book Review: Survival of the Sickest|url=http://www.patheos.com/blogs/daylightatheism/2007/03/survival-of-the-sickest/|publisher=Patheos}}</ref>\n\nThe book debuted on the ''New York Time''s bestselling book list in hardcover nonfiction.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hardcover Nonfiction|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/04/books/bestseller/0304besthardnonfiction.html?_r=0|work=New York Times}}</ref>\n\n===''How Sex Works:  Why We Look, Smell, Taste, Feel, and Act the Way We Do''===\nIn April 2009, Dr. Moalem's second book ''How Sex Works: Why We Look, Smell, Taste, Feel, and Act the Way We Do'' was published by [[HarperCollins]].<ref name=oprah2>{{cite web|last=Winter|first=Jessica|title=Between the Covers|url=http://www.oprah.com/omagazine/How-Sex-Works-by-Sharon-Moalem-Book-Review|publisher=Oprah}}</ref> The book examines the scientific reasons why people are attracted to one another.<ref name=time/> The topics covered include the evolutionary underpinnings of [[sexual attraction]], [[monogamy]], and [[sexual orientation]].<ref name=abc>{{cite web|title=EXCERPT: 'How Sex Works'|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/Books/story?id=7472408|publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref name=wp/><ref name=tbt>{{cite web|last=Miller|first=Jen A.|title=Review: 'How Sex Works: Why We Look, Smell, Taste, Feel, and Act the Way We Do,' by Dr. Sharon Moalem|url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/health/review-how-sex-works-why-we-look-smell-taste-feel-and-act-the-way-we-do/1003125|publisher=Tampa Bay Times|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202122205/http://www.tampabay.com/news/health/review-how-sex-works-why-we-look-smell-taste-feel-and-act-the-way-we-do/1003125|archivedate=2014-02-02}}</ref>\n\n===''Inheritance:  How Our Genes Change Our Lives\u2014And Our Lives Change Our Genes''===\nIn April 2014, ''Inheritance'' was published by Grand Central Publishing.<ref>{{cite web |title=Inheritance by Sharon Moalem MD, PhD |url=https://www.grandcentralpublishing.com/titles/sharon-moalem-md-phd/inheritance/9781455549450/ |website=Grand Central Publishing}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Velasquez-Manoff |first1=Moises |title=MIND Reviews: Inheritance |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/mind-reviews-inheritance/ |publisher=Scientific American}}</ref> The book, co-written by journalist Matthew D. LaPlante, unpacks emerging research into the flexible genome, which is \"mediated and orchestrated by how you live, where you live, the stresses you face, and the things you consume,\u201d promising a future in which people will make health decisions not based on what is good for most of the people most of the time, but rather what is genetically best for each individual based on their specific genetic and epigenetic profile. Inheritance was named one of Amazon's Best Science Books of 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leopold |first1=Todd |title=Amazon picks the 100 best books of 2014 |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2014/11/10/living/amazon-100-best-books-2014-ng/index.html |publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\n===''The Better Half: On the Genetic Superiority of Women''===\n\n''The Better Half'' was published in April 2020 by [[Farrar, Straus and Giroux]] and by [[Allen Lane]] (an imprint of [[Penguin Books]]) in the United Kingdom.<ref name=sundaytimes></ref> Prior to publication, ''The Better Half'' was named one of the non-fiction books to look out for in 2020 by the ''[[Guardian]], [[Evening Standard]]'' and the ''[[Sunday Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hampson |first1=Laura |title=World Book Day: the best books to look forward to in 2020 |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/books/best-books-coming-out-in-2020-a4324796.html |publisher=Evening Standard}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Holgate |first1=Andrew |title=The Sunday Times books to watch out for in 2020 |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/2020-what-to-watch-out-for-next-year-sunday-times-books-gb2dwht8s |publisher=The Sunday Times}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sharkey |first1=Lauren |title=9 Investigative Non-Fiction Books To Sink Your Teeth Into In 2020 |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/9-investigative-non-fiction-books-to-sink-your-teeth-into-in-2020-21735801 |publisher=Bustle}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2020 in books |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2020/jan/04/2020-in-books-a-literary-calendar |publisher=The Guardian}}</ref> In the book Moalem argues that from birth, genetic females possess a survival advantage that results from them being the [[homogametic]] sex that have inherited two X chromosomes, as opposed to genetic males who are the [[heterogametic]] sex with one X and Y chromosome.<ref name=sundaytimes></ref> Moalem explains that not only do genetic females have more genetic information than males, but that female cells using different X chromosomes can interact and cooperate, which gives them an advantage throughout the life course and especially in times of [[famine]] and [[pandemic]]s.<ref name=newstatesman>{{cite web |last1=Bootle |first1=Emily |title=The female of the species is more healthy than the male Physician Sharon Moalem on the role our sex chromosomes play in immunity and genetic advantage. |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/health/2020/04/female-species-more-healthy-male |website=New Statesman}}</ref> Moalem's assertion regarding the female survival advantage became apparent during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], where males were found to have a higher mortality rate reported across many age groups.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moalem |first1=Sharon |title=Why Are So Many More Men Dying from Coronavirus? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/02/opinion/coronavirus-men-women.html |publisher=The New York Times |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Schumaker |first1=Erin |title=COVID-19 mortality twice as high for men in Italy as women |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/covid-19-mortality-high-men-italy-women/story?id=69717021 |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ahuja |first1=Anjana |title=When it comes to coronavirus, men are more vulnerable  Differences in immune function appear to start straight out of the womb |url=https://www.ft.com/content/a32e62b4-4be9-11ea-95a0-43d18ec715f5 |publisher=Financial Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Devlin |first1=Hannah |title=Men are much more likely to die from coronavirus - but why? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/men-are-much-more-likely-to-die-from-coronavirus-but-why |publisher=The Guardian |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rabin |first1=Roni Caryn |title=In Italy, Coronavirus Takes a Higher Toll on Men |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/20/health/coronavirus-italy-men-risk.html |publisher=The New York Times |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The book also explicates that female immunological superiority is rooted in them being the homogametic sex as well as being aided by the fact that [[estrogens]] are thought to be able to stimulate the immune system, while [[androgens]] such as testosterone have been found to suppress the immune system of males.<ref name=sundaytimes></ref> Moalem further explicates that the result of the more robust immune system that females posses provides an explanation for the much higher rate of [[autoimmune disorders]] observed in females.<ref name=newstatesman></ref> In the final chapter of the book, Moalem argues why sex chromosomes matter in medicine as he calls for a long-overdue reconsideration of our male-centric, one-size-fits-all view of the body, a view that even today continues to frame women through the lens of men.<ref name=sundaytimes></ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://sharonmoalem.com\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moalem, Sharon}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American geneticists]]\n[[Category:University of Toronto alumni]]\n[[Category:Mount Sinai School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish physicians]]\n[[Category:American physicians]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGuardian(link changed toThe Guardian) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sharon_Moalem"}
